<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Protection of Chinese Indonesians' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese newspaper urges
the Indonesian authorities to protect the legitimate rights of the
ethnic Chinese in Indonesia and punish those who brutalized the
minority group in a series of riots.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary for its Monday edition, the People's Daily says
that thousands of shops owned by Chinese Indonesians were
ransacked and many ethnic Chinese women were reported to have been
savagely raped in the riots, which occurred in May.
</P>
<P>
These criminal acts have sparked grave concern and strong
indignation among the people in China and the overseas Chinese
societies.
</P>
<P>
The international community strongly condemned these
atrocities, describing them as being "savage" and "inhuman" and a
blasphemy against modern civilization.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government expressed its deep concern over the
unjust treatment of the ethnic Chinese and the Chinese nationals
living there and urged the Indonesian government to bring to
justice those held accountable and prevent the occurrence of
similar incidents.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that the Chinese Indonesians are law-abiding
people, who have made important contributions to the economic
development and social progress in that country.
</P>
<P>
At the critical moment when the Indonesian economy is in
serious trouble, the ethnic Chinese are still making unremitting
efforts to help lift that country out of the economic predicament
and maintain its social stability.
</P>
<P>
The legitimate rights of the ethnic Chinese, who constitute an
important part of the Indonesian society, should be well respected
and their lives and property be effectively protected, the paper
says.
</P>
<P>
But what they got is just the opposite, it notes.
</P>
<P>
Although Indonesian President B.J. Habibie admitted the
incidents as being "the most inhuman event in the history of the
nation" and pledged no such incidents would happen again, the
paper notes, some people in Indonesia have been playing down the
gravity of these incidents and even denied their occurrence.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that this is an important reason why similar
incidents are still happening even today.
</P>
<P>
The paper urges the Indonesian authorities to face the facts
squarely, take strong steps to punish the lawless and protect the
personal safety and property of the ethnic Chinese, and treat
them fairly.
</P>
<P>
This will help Indonesia restore its credibility in the
international community so that it can attract investment,
stablize the society and secure an early economic recovery and
development, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
