<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- After reaching a settlement with Italy's "BBD"
Arms Company, the United Arab Emirates (UAE) decided to lift the
embargo imposed on the Italian arms companies.
</P>
<P>
Under the new decision, the Italian companies are allowed to
supply the UAE armed forces with defensive weaponry, the UAE news
agency reported in the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In March last year, the UAE decided to ban the importing of
arms from the Italian arms companies in response to BBD's refusal
to take part in repairing a technical impairment in the missile
launchers purchased from the company at 280 million U.S. dollars
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Moroccan oil imports in the first five months this
year stood at 2.4 billion dirhams (2.1 billion U.S. dollars),
compared with 3.4 billion dirhams (2.9 billion dollars) of the
same period last year, according to the latest official figures.
</P>
<P>
Over the first half of this year, the Moroccan economy achieved
a 5.3 percent Gross Domestic Product growth.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Two foreign companies are competing to buy 40 percent
shares of the Jordan Telecommunications Company (JTC), which is to
be privatized under a government plan, the Jordan Times reported
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official daily quoted a government source as saying
that the British Cable and Wireless Company has offered 320
million U.S. dollars for the shares and the Southern Bell Company
of the United States offered more than 600 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government decided in 1997 to sell 26 percent of
JTC's shares to a strategic partner in a bid to draw private
investments, update technology, establish incentive management
mechanism and increase the company's profits. The privatization
scope was later grew to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Defying a national anti-smoking campaign, Egypt's
tobacco giant the Eastern Tobacco Company has decided to increase
its production this year, the English-language daily Egyptian
Gazette reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the Eastern Tobacco Company will increase its
production to 60 billion cigarettes in 1998 from 54.8 billion
cigarettes last year.
</P>
<P>
That means it will produce an average of 164.4 million
cigarettes daily, or 2.74 cigarettes for every citizen.
</P>
<P>
To further boost its sale among domestic smokers who account
for one ninth of the whole population, the state-run company is
planning to launch new brands in the local market by the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
The company, which has a monopoly on the domestic market, is
doing a brisk business outside as well. It has clinched deals with
Russia and Ukraine to export 250 million cigarettes to these
former Soviet states.
</P>
<P>
It has also received orders to supply the U.S. market with 12
million Egyptian pounds (3.5 million U.S. dollars) worth of
cigarettes, and provide 20 million pounds (5.9 million dollars)
worth of cigarettes and tobacco to Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
With all the plans, the company seems set to run counter to
the government-sponsored campaign aimed to alert Egyptians of the
dangers of smoking.
</P>
<P>
Hamdi al-Sayyed, head of the National Association of Physicians
said Friday the government has earmarked 300,000 U.S. dollars for
a tobacco awareness campaign targeting juveniles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
