<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief Leaves for Libya to Tackle Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid left for Libya Sunday for talks on the
recent U.S.-British discussion on holding the trial for the two
alleged Lockerbie bombers in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid is expected to seek response of Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi to a detailed plan for the procedures of the trial
of the two Libyans suspected of planting a bomb on an American
airliner that killed 270 when the aircraft blew up over the
Scottish town of Lockerbie in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. agreed last month to allow the two
suspects to stand trial in the Netherlands but under Scottish law
with Scottish judges, rather than an international panel of judges.
</P>
<P>
Tripoli is likely to seek the AL's support for lifting the
U.N. embargo immediately upon its approval of the trial procedures.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations slapped an air embargo against Libya in 1992
after Tripoli refused to hand over the two suspects for trial in
either Britain or the U.S., arguing that this will compromise
their chance for a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
The AL General Secretariat sources said that Abdel-Meguid, who
departed from Egyptian northern port city of Alexandria Sunday,
traveled to Libya by land, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief has requested permission Tuesday to fly to Libya,
but the U.N. Sanctions Committee which monitors the air sanctions
on Libya turned down the request Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The AL General Secretariat issued a statement Saturday,
criticizing the committee's objection to the request, arguing that
the AL chief was to find all possible means to solve the
long-running crisis.
</P>
<P>
Following the compromise of the U.S. and Britain, the AL chief
has expressed his readiness to help peacefully resolve the dispute
in a way that would guarantee the rights of all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
The AL has supported Libya's stance, and suggested a fair trial
in a neutral venue.
</P>
<P>
In a recent meeting in Cairo, the AL said Libya was entitled to
claim damages for the havoc resulting from the unfair sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The recent compromise of the U.S. and Britain came amid
increasing defiance of U.N. sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of the African Unity Organization has
threatened to bust the embargo as of September 1 should Washington
and London fail to agree on a compromise.
</P>
<P>
Three African heads of state have recently defied the embargo
by flying to Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
