<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Warns Against Overstretching Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Sunday warned that the Palestinians' patience is running
thin against Israel's continued resistance to a U.S. initiative to
save the Mideast peace-making.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. offer (of Israeli troop withdrawal from 13.1 percent
of the West Bank) is a good initiative. It is already accepted by
the Palestinians but they could not wait for long," Moussa told
reporters following a meeting with President Hosni Mubarak in the
northern coastal resort of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the peace process has entered a "vicious circle"
without any hope of progress now or in the future.
</P>
<P>
"The elements and potentials of such progress are not clear
under the current Israeli policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Palestinian negotiators have set
Monday as the deadline for their Israeli counterparts to make
progress on the long-stalled peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Direct talks have been going on for two weeks between Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Secretary General of
Palestine Liberation Organization Executive Committee Mahmoud
Abbas (Abu Mazen) on the U.S. proposal to get the peace process
back on track, but there have been no signs of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians broke down in
March 1997 after Israel began to construct a new Jewish
neighborhood in Arab East Jerusalem which the Palestinians want to
be their future capital.
</P>
<P>
"What is going on is merely a matter of procrastination, delay
and waste of time without any sign of progress," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The international community should not stand as spectator to the
peace initiative as it collapses, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also briefed Mubarak on the outcome of his talks in
Paris last week to propel the Egyptian-French initiative on
holding an international peace conference, along with results of
the meetings held by Al Quds (Jerusalem) Committee of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference last week in Casablanca,
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's trip to Paris has reportedly turned the idea into a
plan and thrashed out details of a viable option to the ongoing
U.S. mediation bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Leaders Urged to Help Revive Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian leadership,
under the chairmanship of Yasser Arafat, called on the world
leaders on Sunday to help revive the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
This call was made in the letters sent Sunday to the world
leaders, especially the co-sponsors of the peace process, namely
the U.S. and Russia, European Union nations, China and japan,
according to Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC).
</P>
<P>
In the letters, the Palestinian leadership put together all
the facts about Israeli exercise in the peace process and
explained the ongoing Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks have been continued in an endless circle
without achieving any results, the letters said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership, in the letters, renewed their call
on the United States to officially announce its initiative, which
asks Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank during
the second stage troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Washington has not announced the initiative, already accepted
by the Palestinians, due to Israel's opposition.
</P>
<P>
The leadership denounced the Israeli government's decision to
create armed militias in the settlements, saying the continuation
of settler's daily provocations and attacks against the
Palestinians and their property will result in an explosion of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The leadership met in Gaza Saturday night and decided to send
the letters to the world leaders to tell them the true picture of
the peace process, said JMCC.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership consists of government ministers and
members of the Executive Committee of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
