<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Interior Minister Appointed Acting Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader Sunday
appointed Interior Minister Abdolvahed Mousavi Lari as acting
commander of the security forces for better coordination between
the executive body and the security officials.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was made in reply to a request made by Lari to
give him free hand to coordinate the executive body with the
security officials, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, also
commander-in-chief of the armed forces, Lari said that the mandate
would enable him to carry out his responsibility for providing
public security and putting into practice the security programs.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the interior ministry and the security
forces were strained after the government of the moderate cleric
President Mohammad Khatami came to power a year ago as Khamenei
did not appoint former Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri as the
acting commander of the forces as usual.
</P>
<P>
In the past, upon the request of the interior minister, the
leader normally appointed him as the acting commander of the
security forces, but Nouri was not appointed because he did not
request during his 10-month tenure.
</P>
<P>
Nouri was impeached and sacked on June 21 by the
conservative-dominated Majlis (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
After Lari gained a vote of confidence from the Majlis to
succeed Nouri, moderate newspapers demanded the security forces
to come under the command of the interior ministry in order to
prevent any disorder in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution, the interior ministry is
responsible for law and order in the country and security at the
borders. It issues permission for demonstrations, rallies and
activities of political parties and organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
