<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Labor Delegation Heads for U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of Israeli
opposition Labor Party headed by its Chairman Ehud Barak left for
Washington on Sunday, seeking to revive the stalled Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
During their week-long visit, the delegation will explain to
the U.S. government, the Congress and leaders of major Jewish
organization Labor's position on the peace march and ask
Washington to publicize its initiative on Israeli troops
redeployment in the West Bank, a senior Labor source said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told Xinhua
that the delegation will hold talks with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern
Affairs Martin Indyk, U.S. Middle East Peace Envoy Dennis Ross,
and National Security Advisor Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
They may also meet President Bill Clinton, the source disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The trip is organized at the request of U.S. Jewish leaders who
complained to Labor Party leaders that the Party's position and
voice about the peace process are not heard in the U.S., the
source added.
</P>
<P>
Labor legislator Ephraim Sneh said he and his colleagues go to
the U.S. "so that they (the Americans) will know that in Israel at
least half the nation has a different view on the issue of peace
from that of the government of Israel."
</P>
<P>
The Labor party, which oversaw the signing of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace agreements in 1993 and 1995, narrowly
lost Israel's 1996 elections to Likud by less than 1 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition in Israel supports Israeli troops
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Key Labor Party member Yossi Beilin also said "We think it's
important the Americans make public their pullback plan, so that
we, as well as the Israeli public, get a clear picture. It's
difficult to support an initiative which has not been released for
publication."
</P>
<P>
Israel's ruling Likud Party officials on Saturday accused
Labor's leaders of going to cause damage to the government's
policy over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Uzi Landau, a senior Likud lawmaker, said the Labor leaders
were trying to get the Americans to put pressure on Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to make concessions at a critical stage of
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has proposed Israel to hand over 13.1 percent of the
West Bank to the Palestinians during its second troops
redeployment. The Palestinians accepted the proposal, but Israel
rejected it, citing security reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
