<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Terms Iran's Missiles Long-Term Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli military chief
reiterated Sunday that Iran's efforts to develop missiles and
non-conventional weapons pose a long-term threat to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of Israeli Armed Forces Shaul Mofaz made
the remarks during a visit to the army's Home Front Command,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The threat necessitates special budget allocations for the
Israeli army and its Home Front Command to boost their defense
ability, he said.
</P>
<P>
On July 25, Iran confirmed that it has successfully testfired a
medium-range missile with a range of 1,300 kilometers, which means
that the Shihab-3 missile can reach Israel and the U.S. forces
stationed in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Shihab-3 will be fully-operational
within a year.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Assistant U.S. Secretary of State Martin Indyk
warned that Iran is working on a more flexible long-range missile
Shihab-4, with a range of 2,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which regards Iran as an arch-enemy in the Middle East,
has expressed grave concern over the test and warned that Iran's
ability to develop these kinds of weapons poses a threat not only
to Israel, but also to other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Iranian news agency IRNA reported that Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami on Saturday defended Iran's defense program,
including the recent missile tests.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said Iran's military strength "by no means constitutes
a threat to the security of other countries, but rather
contributes to the security of friendly countries as well as the
Muslim world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
