<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-02 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Hardliners Make Concession, Lifting Ban on Moderate Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary
made a concession Sunday by conditionally lifting the ban on a
moderate daily after it keeps publishing under a new name.
</P>
<P>
Public Relation Director of the Tehran Justice Department
Saeed Nobari said that Tehran's public court has issued a decree
to lift the ban on the Tous, provided it distances itself from its
banned predecessor Jameah (Society), the official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
Tous, named after an ancient Iranian city, was banned
Saturday, but it was published under a new name Aftab Emrouz, or
the Sun Today, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The publication of Aftab Emrouz showed the determination of the
moderates to uphold freedom of expression advocated by President
Mohammad Khatami and not to give up to the powerful conservatives
who dominate the legislative and judiciary bodies.
</P>
<P>
Tous hit the newsstands only on July 25 to replace the Jameah
by absorbing Jameah's staff. Its publication angered conservatives.
</P>
<P>
A group of hard-liners on Saturday attacked the office of Tous,
beating up its editor-in-chief Mashallah Shamsolwaezin, and even
threatening to kill him.
</P>
<P>
Nobari said Tous was banned because it has violated the
publication law by using a similar form to that of the banned
daily Jameah, which was closed down on July 24.
</P>
<P>
Following thorough investigation of the court, he said,
Managing Director of the daily Mohammad Sadeq Javad Hesar was
fined 10 million rials (1,818 U.S. dollars) according to the
press laws and the Islamic penal laws.
</P>
<P>
As the violator presented no objections to the court ruling,
the final verdict was announced to the Ministry of Culture and
Islamic Guidance to allow the paper continue its publication in a
different format from the banned Jameah, Nobari said.
</P>
<P>
Conservative leaders, including the judiciary head Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi, have lashed out at the Minister of Culture and
Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani for giving green light to
Tous' publication.
</P>
<P>
However, Mohajerani argued that the country's current press
laws did not ban the staff of a banned daily from transferring to
another daily.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance Saturday demanded
the judiciary revoke its ban on Tous, arguing that the points
adduced against the publisher of the daily by the court have
already been fully explained to him and he has been committed to
observing those criteria in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
