<HEADLINE> Gunfire Rings in Eastern D.R. Congo at Rwandan Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The rebel forces supported by
Rwandan troops and the government forces of the Democratic
Republic of Congo Sunday exchanged gunfire in Goma, the capital of
the Nord-Kivu in eastern part of the country and at the border
with Rwanda, said reports from Goma.
</P>
<P>
The Goma airport was also closed for security reasons, said
official sources here.
</P>
<P>
The fighting erupted after D.R. Congo President Laurent-Desire
Kabila ordered on July 27 the withdrawal of Rwanda soldiers who
have been staying in D.R. Congo since they helped him come into
power 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
This signaled an apparent split between the D.R. Congo with
Rwanda and Uganda, the two eastern neighbors which intervened in
former Zaire and helped topple the regime of Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said in a speech on Monday to the leaders of the
country's military that he had decided to expel all the remaining
Rwandan soldiers from the country.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that some 800 Rwandan soldiers had returned
home from the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The rebel forces seem to be members of the Banyamulenge Tutsi
minority who were the first to start the war against Mobutu in
late 1996.
</P>
<P>
A senior military official said that the fighting was started
by the Rwandan soldiers who refused to go home.
</P>
<P>
The officer, who wished to remain anonymous, said that the
Congolese army is now in control of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The private Rwandan news agency Monday carried a communique by
a rebellious movement against Kabila, which said that it had
launched a war against the D.R. Congo government in Nord Kivu.
</P>
<P>
The communique, broadcast Sunday from Goma and Bukavu on the
national Congolese radio the Voix du Peuple, was read by the
commander of the 10th battalion of the Congolese army based in
Goma, Sylvain Mbuchi.
</P>
<P>
"The province of Nord-Kivu has entered a state of open
rebellion against the government of Laurent-Desire Kabila. In the
name of the government troops we denounce the regime of
Laurent-Desire Kabila,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He listed the ``errors'' allegedly committed by Kabila as being
``nepotism, corruption and bad government''. 
</P>
</TEXT>
