<HEADLINE> Yangtze Flood Situation Remains Serious (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The water level at Shashi in Hubei Province stood 43.48 meters
by 14:00 this afternoon, 0.37 meter over Sunday, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, water levels in the middle and lower reaches of the
Yangtze remained high, with the level in Hankou rising slightly to
29.06 meters by 14:00 today, and reaching a record 16.3 meters at
Datong in Anhui Province this morning at 08:00 this morning.
</P>
<P>
Water conservancy experts attributed this year's Yangtze
flooding, the heaviest since 1954, to unseasonably heavy rains
sweeping through the entire Yangtze River Valley since early
summer, and created even more serious silting which has
significantly filled the riverbed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
High-ranking Chinese leaders, including President Jiang Zemin
and Premier Zhu Rongji, have exhibited great concerns about flood
control efforts along the Yangtze, and Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao is
currently heading the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The staff daily flood briefings planning meetings attended by
officials from the Ministry of Water Resources and other relevant
central departments, senior flood control officials and retired
water conservancy experts.
</P>
<P>
The Headquarters has called on the over two million people and
soldiers who have maintained a constant vigil along 3,500-km of
levees in the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze over the
past several weeks to remain on a high state of alert and extend
every possible effort to ensure the success this year's flood
control effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
