<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Sets to Tackle Economic Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli is taking measures to
remedy the economic slowdown, primarily the rising unemployment,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is setting up a national
economic council to tackle the issue.
</P>
<P>
The new council will comprise top officials from the Bank of
Israel, the ministries of finance, industry and trade, labor and
social affairs, as well as the Manufacturers Association and the
Histadrut (Labor Federation).
</P>
<P>
The radio said Netanyahu announced Monday that the council will
meet for the first time this week, and he will present new
measures dealing with the economic situation at the next cabinet
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The plan to set up the council came at a time when the
government released one discouraging data after another on the
economy recently.
</P>
<P>
A senior member of the Manufacturers Association predicted
Sunday that the economy in Israel will grow by only 1.1 percent in
1998, the lowest growth rate since 1966.
</P>
<P>
This echoed a prediction early June by the Economist
Intelligence Unit which said the Asian crisis, the continuing
slump in tourism and a steep fall in investment will push the
economic growth in Israel this year down to a 32-year low.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data released by the Central Bureau of
Statistics, unemployment rate hit a five-year high of 9.3 percent
in May. Meanwhile, experts said this trend of steadily rising
jobless rate will not reverse itself soon.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman, who has been under fire for
the government's economic policy, said his ministry has been
working for weeks in a bid to find a solution to rising
unemployment. He insisted the government would continue allowing
the private sector to develop and grow and to serve as an engine
for the whole economy.
</P>
<P>
Under criticism that its high interest, low inflation policy
should be blamed for the lingering economic slowdown and rising
unemployment, the Bank of Israel, the central bank, announced late
July that it will cut interest rates by another 0.3 percentage
point in August to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Since inflation has been kept at a relatively low level of 4
percent, the Bank of Israel has cut the interest rates seven times
in months. Altogether, the rates have fallen by 2.4 percentage
points since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
But Neeman stressed that to maintain the stability of the
Israeli currency, the shekel, the interest rates could not be
slashed too quickly.
</P>
<P>
Not everyone, however, has confidence in the new economic
council. Maxim Levy, member of the parliament's Labor and Social
Affairs Committee, said that similar councils had been set up in
the past, but they did not help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
