<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze Flood Situation Remains Serious (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese meteorologist said
today that this year's second tropical storm, expected to hit land
in China's southeast coastal regions within the next two days,
will quite likely have some negative influence on the flood
control efforts in the lower and middle reaches of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
"We're not as yet able to pinpoint exactly where the typhoon
will hit. However, a landing in provinces such as Jiangsu or
Zhejiang would create greater problems for Yangtze flood control
efforts," said Tang Huifang, vice-president of the Central
Meteorological Station.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed source from the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters said the Yangtze River enbankment, which flood
waters have thoroughly saturated and eroded for over a month, is
now facing a growing threat of breaches.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the flood control situation along the Yangtze
remains extremely serious, and will remain so for the foreseeable
future, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
He said reports indicated the threat of some 3,200 breaches
along the Yangtze, including 1,800 major breaches. Fortunately,
major disasters have thus far been avoided,
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters indicates that heavy rain in southwest China's
Sichuan Province and Chongqing Municipality on August 2 caused
flooding along the Minjiang and Wujiang rivers, both of which are
tributaries of the Yangtze. The flooding also resulted in slowing
rising water levels in thee upper reaches of the Yangtze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
