<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Discusses Customs Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The technical committee in
charge of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) customs union began a
three-day meeting Monday in Riyadh, capital of Saudi Arabia, to
discuss issues concerning customs integration.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency quoted sources at the GCC general
secretariat as saying the committee will discuss the one
crossing-point for imported merchandise from outside the region.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss ways to deal with customs revenues,
customs tariffs on re-exported goods, and ways of protecting
national products.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting of the committee. During its first
meeting last June, it discussed a number of issues including the
timetable for the establishment of GCC tariffs union.
</P>
<P>
The GCC countries are looking forward to achieving such a
union, which reflects the economic prosperity of the member states
as it will provide further freedom to the transportation of goods.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups the six gulf Arab countries of Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
