<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Law Enforcement Undergoes Major Shake-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 212 former members of the
law enforcement departments have been removed from their posts for
unethical or illegal conduct.
</P>
<P>
The major shake-up represents an educational and reorganization
move on the part of the Ministry of Justice to check injustices in
prisons and correctional institutes, and unethical practices
involving lawyers, notaries and grass roots legal service units,
as well as legal departments
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,146 cases have been reported in 17 provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities, with investigations carried
out on 738 cases and 75 people prosecuted for misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The leadership reorganization has been carried out in legal
departments at all levels, with improvements in rules, regulations
and management mechanisms, and strengthened supervision introduced
to future corruption.
</P>
<P>
The recent move by the Ministry of Justice is viewed as another
major government endeavor to curb rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
Unethical and illegal behavior in law enforcement has been the
focus of public outrage in recent years, as evidenced by the fact
that the issue ranks as one of the major complaints tabled during
the annual sessions of the National People's Congress, China's top
legislature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
