<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Unilaterally Declares Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government
unilaterally declared a ceasefire with rebels in southern Sudan on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The truce will start on Tuesday, said a government statement,
but without mentioning the duration of the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the ceasefire was announced "to contain the
humanitarian situation in southern Sudan," where at least 1
million people are facing starvation.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came on the eve of negotiations between the
warring parties in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia with an aim to end the
15-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese People's Liberation Army led by John Garang is now
the only rebel group continuing fighting the government for
autonomy of the predominantly Christian and animist region from the
Muslim north. In April last year, six rebel factions signed a
peace treaty with the government to end their armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
At least 1.5 million people have died since the insurgence
started in 1983.
</P>
<P>
There are about 2.6 million people in southern Sudan suffering
from lack of food. Fighting and drought are making the situation
worse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
