<HEADLINE> Philippine President Meets U.S. Defense Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Monday met with visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William S.
Cohen, assuring him that the Presidential Palace will push for the
ratification of the proposed Visiting Forces Agreement between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting in the Presidential Palace, Estrada said it
is "necessary" and "beneficial" for the two countries to resume
joint military exercises, for which the proposed agreement will
pave the way.
</P>
<P>
The proposed agreement, signed early this year by the two
governments, is pending in the Philippine Senate for approval. The
controversial accord spells out the legal status and rights of
U.S. military personnel in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said in a press conference after meeting with President
Estrada that the U.S.-Philippine relations go beyond the Visiting
Forces Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to maintain good relations with the Philippine
government should this agreement not be successful. Our
relationship falls well beyond the agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed optimism earlier that the Philippine
Senate will ratify the agreement as it will help Manila and
Washington work in partnership for the stability of the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"The Visiting Forces Agreement is going to help the United
States and the Philippines work more closely together and I would
like to be clear on this point, the U.S. does not seek any bases
in the Philippines," he said after holding talks with Philippine
Defense Secretary Orlando S. Mercado.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is an expanded mutual security relationship with
the Philippines. That is why our government supports the
agreement," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
