<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Khatami's First Year in Office Features </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Treading a rough and thorny path,
Iran's moderate President Mohammad Khatami on Monday completed his
first year of office marked with diplomatic successes as well as
domestic political setbacks.
</P>
<P>
When the liberal-minded Khatami sworn in as the president, high
hopes were pinned on him to bring the Islamic Gulf state out of
long years of its enstrangement from the world.
</P>
<P>
Khatami did not let his people down. His government's focus on
detente with the rest of the world and the rule of law inside the
country has won compliments from both home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Distancing from the hard-line stance of his predecessors,
Khatami based his foreign policy the principles of removing
tensions with other countries, developing bilateral relations on
the basis of mutual respect and strengthening peace and stability
in the region as well as the world.
</P>
<P>
The overture of detente not only convinced the neighboring
countries, the Gulf states in particular, to remove long-running
misunderstandings to open the way for friendly cooperation, but
also was welcomed by Tehran's sworn enemy, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Following the successful Islamic summit in Tehran last
December, Arab countries, led by Egypt and Saudi Arabia, extended
their hands to Iran and agreed to sink their old feuds to usher in
a new era of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Iran's longtime foe Iraq also agreed to accelerate the pace of
solving the remaining issues left over from the 1980-88 bloody war
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
European nations, putting aside their concerns about Iran's
stands on terrorism, the Middle East peace process, human rights
and weapons of mass destruction, rushed to Tehran to examine
opportunities of investment.
</P>
<P>
Most notably, the U.S. also waved olive branches to Tehran for
a possible reapproachment after nearly 20 years of
confrontation. In a positive sign, the exchange of visits by
sports people was regarded as a prelude to an end to the
two-decade hostility between them.
</P>
<P>
Back home, Khatami's liberal reforms have not gone as smoothly
as expected due to the strong resistance from the powerful
conservatives who dominate the judiciary and the society.
</P>
<P>
His slogan of "rule of law" and policy of granting more
personal freedom to the people has been denounced as an attempt to
undermine the Islamic rule and values.
</P>
<P>
The first major setback was the impeachment of his leading
supporter Abdollah Nouri as the interior minister by the
conservative-dominated Mjalis (Parliament) in June.
</P>
<P>
The imprisonment of the liberal Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein
Karbaschi by the court for alleged corruption was another blow
against Khatami in an intensified battle between the two camps.
</P>
<P>
Despite the setbacks, Khatami has scored points by successively
selling the idea of "rule of law" to his people, which has been
accepted by nearly all political factions -- in public at least.
</P>
<P>
And Khatami's reformist policies enjoy considerable support
among the society, the youths in particular, who endorse his
outlooks on political and social developments.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, a continued fall in world oil prices had
cornered the heavily oil-dependent Iran. But Khatami is striving
to manage a way out, announcing a rehabilitation plan on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The plan is widely regarded as an indication that Khatami's
focus for the coming years will be on economic reform and
development.
</P>
<P>
However, observers said, the conservatives would be well in
Khatami's way so long as he keeps the reforms on, a harbinger of
further ups and downs, if not successes and setbacks, for the
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
