<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Speaker Calls for Strong Central Organ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Speaker Dawit
Yohannes said Monday a revitalized central organ with stronger
mandate and broader policy options must continue to guide
Africans in monitoring and responding to its crisis.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 10th annual conference of the African Society of
International and Comparative Law here, Dawit said "our
collective political will and aspiration must manifest itself in
stronger political action."
</P>
<P>
"To that end, the prevention of armed conflicts must dictate
our organization's highest goal, deepest commitment and greatest
ambition," the speaker said.
</P>
<P>
To find so many of Africa's people languishing in abject
poverty when Africa stand poised to enter the next millennium is
not only unacceptable, but also dangerous, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, peace, democracy, good governance and
respect for human rights cannot flourish amongst human tragedy
and suffering.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Anatone Thendrebeogo, assistant secretary general
of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), expressed OAU's
support for the success of the conference on behalf of OAU
Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim.
</P>
<P>
The OAU would continue its efforts to solve the conflicts of
the continent, improve injustice and promote human rights,
democracy and good governance.
</P>
<P>
A message by the U.N. Chief Kofi Annan said regional practices
provide a valid basis for the codification and progressive
development of international law at the international level.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference will be devoted to the analysis of
the achievement and prospect of the OAU at its 35th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also focus on topics such as political
achievements, peacekeeping, conflict prevention, human rights,
economic integration and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The African Society of International and Comparative Law is a
non-governmental organization in the region which was established
in 1986. 
</P>
