<HEADLINE> China Vows to Strengthen Economic Ties, Trade With Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- China has given top priority to
Sino-African economic relations and trade of equality and mutual
benefit, State Councillor Wu Yi said today at the opening ceremony
of the China-Africa Seminar for Economic and Management Officials.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, hosted by China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) and Foreign Ministry, is the first
of its kind and was created by the suggestion of Chinese President
Jiang Zemin. It will be held twice a year for economic officials
of African countries.
</P>
<P>
Wu welcomed the 22 participants from 12 countries attending the
seminar, saying she aimed to inform participants about China's
basic situation, introduce each other to their own countries, and
deepen mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the first seminar were from Egypt, Eritrea,
Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya, Mozambique, Namibia, Nigeria, Sudan,
Tanzania, Uganda and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
China places importance on the development of sincere and
friendly relations with Africa of equality, mutual benefit and
cooperation, Wu Yi said.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to strive with all African countries to
develop a long-term, stable relationship of comprehensive
cooperation oriented toward the 21st century, she said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of China-Africa economic relations and trade, she said
the Chinese government has always valued its commercial ties with
African countries. Both Chinese leaders who have visited Africa
and leaders of African countries who have visited China promised
to give top priority to foster economic and commercial cooperation
of equality and mutual benefit, she said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between China and Africa has continued to grow in recent
years. Records show that the trade volume was 5.67 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997, up 40.6 percent over the previous year, and
six times the 1990 figure. The volume for the first six months of
this year reached 2.859 billion U.S. dollars, rising 12 percent,
including a 44 percent increase in exports. Various channels, ways
and multi-levels appeared in the bilateral trade ties, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Growth of its trade with Africa created very favorable
conditions for further development of bilateral trade ties, which
still has a large potential, she said.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to join hands with African countries, and to
strive to upgrade China-Africa commercial ties to a new height,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, the MOFTEC minister, also delivered a speech at
the ceremony. He said that during the seminars Chinese
governmental officials and experts are expected to introduce to
the participants China's way of economic development, its economic
structural reforms, and policies and initiatives in all fields
since reforms and opening-up began, especially the policies of
attracting foreign investment and strengthening economic ties and
trade with Africa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, participants will exchange information on the status
and experience of economic development in their own countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will also organize the participants
touring China for investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Foreign Minister Ji Peiding and diplomatic envoys of
relevant African countries also attended today's ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
