<HEADLINE> Ung Huot Urges Cambodians to Respect People's Will </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian First Prime Minister
Ung Huot on Monday asked Cambodians "not to create problems" but
to respect the people's will following last Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at his residence, Ung Huot said
he would hand over power if his Reastr Niyum (Populism) Party
failed in the election.
</P>
<P>
Initial results showed that Ung Huot's party, failing to pocket
enough votes, would not have any seat in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot vowed to "respect the will of the people" himself and
called on Cambodians to "put the national interests above
everything else".
</P>
<P>
He said he has decided to "conditionally" accept the results
pending investigations into alleged vote frauds.
</P>
<P>
"I will accept the final result after the investigation and
verification by the National Election Committee (NEC)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot's party was among those calling for a probe into
"irregularities" which were said to have influenced the election
outcome.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP), an apparent winner
of the polls, has named the current co-premier Hun Sen as prime
minister of Cambodia's next coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot replaced his predecessor Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who
was ousted by Hun Sen in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Making his first public remark following the election, Ung Huot
voiced his hope that Cambodia, under the new government, would
have its seat in the United Nations restored and join the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN indefinitely postponed Cambodia's admission following
the ouster of Ranariddh, and Cambodia's UN seat has remained
vacant ever since.
</P>
<P>
The first prime minister also denied press reports that he had
fled to Australia after the election, saying that he had been in
Cambodia before, during and after the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
