<HEADLINE> Public Debates Village Autonomy Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Siyi Ni
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- After reading a recent newspaper
report on the draft revision to the law on the organization of
village committees, Yao Yuan, a Shanghai engineer, immediately
contemplated writing to the top legislature which is
soliciting opinions from the general public.
</P>
<P>
However, Yao refrained from doing so since he is neither a
villager nor a legal expert.
</P>
<P>
"A short time later, I watched a TV news report on Li
Peng's fact-finding tour in the northeast, and was once again
determined to write the letter," said Yao.
</P>
<P>
His letter was one of 452 responses the Legislative Affairs
Committee under the National People's Congress Standing Committee
received last month.
</P>
<P>
Most of the contributors were farmers, village leaders, county
and township government officials, legal experts and ordinary
citizens like Yao.
</P>
<P>
Provincial legislatures expect to receive even more responses
over the next few weeks, according to Zhang Chunshen, deputy
director of the Legislative Affairs Committee. He added that the
Civil Affairs Ministry also received several hundred related
responses.
</P>
<P>
China's 900 million farmers consider the law on the
organization of village committees their "guarantee for autonomy
in village affairs." However, a senior Chinese legislator noted
that the law is "sketchy" and requires refinements and amendments
in terms of application procedures needed to improve village
democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Debates Village Autonomy Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I hope the highest legislative body will continue to solicit
public opinion on all important laws," wrote Lin Kunxian, a
villager from Kanmei Village, Dongshan County, east China's Fujian
Province.
</P>
<P>
He commented that the draft fails to clearly define voting
procedures, and instead simply proposes that ballot boxes must be
monitored by at least two people to prevent fraud.
</P>
<P>
