<HEADLINE> HK Airport Inquiry Progresses Well: Justice Woo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Commission of Inquiry on
the New Airport has made satisfactory progress in its inquiry into
the operation of the new Hong Kong International Airport since it
was appointed on July 21.
</P>
<P>
It has held four meetings and has enlisted the help of lawyers.
The commission has received about 60 boxes of documents and
information from organizations related to the planning and
preparation for the airport, Chairman of the Commission Justice
Woo Kwok-hing said Monday after he visited the airport passenger
terminal, the Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Ltd. and the Asia
Airfreight Terminal Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"Today's initial inspection is very useful to us as we pore
over the document," Justice Woo said.
</P>
<P>
"We shall decide whom to summon as witnesses after we examine
the information. We hope to start open hearings as soon as
possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Justice Woo and Commissioner Edgar Cheng Wai-kin, former
chairman of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, inspected the operation
of Super Terminal 1, run by the Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals
Ltd., the airport's flight information display system and
baggage-handling services to have a preliminary understanding of
problems alleged to have occurred.
</P>
<P>
On assistance from experts, Justice Woo said that Professor
Vincent Yun Shen from the Computer Science Department of the Hong
Kong University of Science and Technology has promised to give
advice on computer systems.
</P>
<P>
Woo reiterated that the two-member commission would do its job
to the utmost and ensure its independence, impartiality and a high
degree of transparency in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The commission was appointed by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
to probe into various matters relating to the operation of the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok, which was opened on July 6 this year.
These matters include the decision to open the airport on July 6,
the planning and preparation for its opening and problems which
arose thereafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
