<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Merapi Volcano Continues to Show Signs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's most active volcano
in Central Java, Mount Merapi, was continuing to show visible
signs of activity with its danger status still one rung below the
highest alert level, Antara News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hot clouds, lava and volcanic ashes had lately also emanated
from the volcano's crater, threatening the lives of people living
on its western and southwestern slopes, Head of the Center for
Research and Development of Volcanic Technology Mas Atje
Purbawinata said.
</P>
<P>
Residents of areas closest to the mountain had been told to
remain alert to any possible emergency as volcanic materials were
continuing to emerge on the mountain's top, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, people in the same areas were now also being
endangered by cold lava floods caused by rains that have been
falling almost continuously in the past few days, he added.
</P>
<P>
The 2,968-meter Merapi erupted on July 11, spilling out hot
fumes and ashes and its conditions have prompted local authorities
to maintain a "Merapi alert" state of readiness.
</P>
<P>
Sixty people were killed when Merapi erupted without warning in
November 1994, while in January last year 8,000 people were
evacuated when it poured out hot gas, ashes and lava. 
</P>
</TEXT>
