<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada appealed anew Monday to former Subic Bay Metropolitan
Chairman Richard Gordon to "step down peacefully."
</P>
<P>
Despite Gordon's continued defiance, Estrada said he has
ordered peacekeeping forces in the freeport to continue exercising
maximum tolerance in dealing with Gordon's supporters.
</P>
<P>
The president renewed his appeal to Gordon's good sense as the
Court of Appeals gave the government and Gordon three days to wrap
up their respective arguments.
</P>
<P>
Estrada charged that Gordon has been resisting a legal order by
the president but still the government will not resort to
violence.
</P>
<P>
It was regrettable, Estrada said, that Gordon's clinging to his
post has led to skirmishes between government forces and his
supporters that cost the life of one person and sent 22 policemen
to hospital with serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
Gordon has served the office for six years. After he failed to
win the May 11 presidential elections, Estrada, who assumed office
on June 30, appointed Felicito Payumo the new Subic Bay
Metropolitan Chairman.
</P>
<P>
Payumo said he has made it clear to the president that he would
vacate his post as soon as the court hands down a ruling in favor
of Gordon.
</P>
<P>
He also assured the president that he would not fall into the
trap set by Gordon who had been allegedly provoking him to use
force against his supporters.
</P>
<P>
But he added that Gordon's alleged supporters are actually
hired hooligans who were engaged to sabotage operations in Subic.
</P>
<P>
Subic was transferred into a freeport and a special economic
zone after U.S. troops withdrew from the naval base in 1992.
</P>
