<HEADLINE> Djibouti Offers to Be Used by Malaysia as Gateway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Djibouti Monday offered
Malaysia to use the African country as a gateway to a huge East
African market of some 130 million people.
</P>
<P>
Djibouti saw this as another way to increase bilateral trade
and investment between the two countries, Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told reporters after a bilateral
delegation meeting between Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and
Djibouti President Hassan Gouled Aptidon here.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said, "Malaysia will send a ministerial level
delegation to the country to have a closer look on this and other
trade and investment opportunities there."
</P>
<P>
The ministers of transport as well as for international trade
and industry would be going to Djibouti for the purpose as
Monday's discussions involved mainly opportunities in the two
sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Djibouti president, who arrived here Sunday for a nine-day
state visit, expressed his country's willingness to provide
various incentives to Malaysian investors in the area of petroleum
industry, telecommunications, banking and light industries,
Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
Djibouti has asked Malaysia to help the country set up a free
trade zone to further develop its economy and wanted Malaysia's
help to modernize and develop its various sectors such as
infrastructure, agriculture, power generation, port and airport
services, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"But the prime minister said that we are currently facing with
economic problems and as such there could be difficulties to
involve in a big way," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
He said Mahathir had offered economic-related training programs
to Djibouti especially in the field of management and port
management.
</P>
<P>
At present, nine students from the republic are studying at the
International Islamic University in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysia and Djibouti Monday signed two agreements,
one on promotion and protection of investment, and the other on
economic, scientific, technical and cultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was represented by Abdullah and International Trade
and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz while Djibouti by Minister of
Commerce and Industry Mohamed Barkat Abdillahi for both
agreements. 
</P>
