<HEADLINE> Sino-Korean Project on Oil Tanker Conversion Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The conversion of a Brazilian oil
supertanker has been successfully finished with the joint efforts
of the Shanhaiguan Shipyard in north China and Hyundai Heavy
Industries Co. Ltd. of the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The supertanker, known as Jose Bonifacio and with
270,000 dead-weight tons, has been re-equipped with a floating,
production, storage and off-loading system (FPSOs). Shanhaiguan
Shipyard and Hyundai converted a similar oil tanker in February.
</P>
<P>
The re-equipment of FPSOs, a very complicated task that requires
the use of high technology, prepares an oil tanker for integrated
tasks of drilling, processing, storing, and off-loading of sea
petroleum.
</P>
<P>
The newly converted tanker, built in 1974, is 337.7 meters
long, 54.5 meters wide, and 28 meters high. It will be operating
on the Marine Sea offshore from Brazil, with a daily production
capacity of 500,000 barrels of crude oil and two million cubic
meters of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1972 and located near the Qinghuangdao Port, the
Shanhaiguan Shipyard is one of the leading shipyards in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
