<HEADLINE> Nepal, Bhutan to Hold Ministerial Talks on Refugee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala said here Monday that Nepal and Bhutan will soon
resume ministerial talks on the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press at the airport upon arrival from
Singapore, Koirala said that during their talks on the sidelines
of the South Asia summit in Colombo, Sri Lanka, he told Chairman
of Bhutanese Council of Ministers Jigme Thinley that "if small
nations can solve their problem, then they can maintain their
identity in the present international context."
</P>
<P>
This time the attitude of the Bhutanese side was positive, he
added.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in eight U.N.-run
camps in eastern Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989
and the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"Refugees can reach everywhere and can do everything when their
problems are not resolved," Koirala said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bhutan have held seven rounds of ministerial talks on
the issue, but to no avail. India has refused to get involved in
the issue, saying it is a bilateral matter.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the 10th summit of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) held on July 29-31,
Koirala also discussed the refugee issue with Indian Prime
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee in addition to bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that the attitude of his Indian counterpart was
positive as well.
</P>
<P>
On the 10th SAARC summit, he said that the summit has shown
that SAARC can play a significant role in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The dispute between India and Pakistan created much commotion
at the SAARC conference and doubts arose about the significance of
SAARC itself," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We stuck to the view that bilateral issues should not
undermine the importance of SAARC and the conference went ahead in
a congenial atmosphere," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the 11th SAARC summit will be held in Nepal at the end
of October or beginning of November 1999.
</P>
<P>
After attending the 10th SAARC summit, Koirala paid a private
visit to Singapore before returning home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
