Monday attacked the handling of foreign policy by the government
led by Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) as a "complete failure",
resulting in "total isolation" of the country following the
nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Initiating a special discussion Monday on the recent
developments affecting India's foreign policy in Lok Sabha, the
Upper House of Parliament, senior Congress leader P. A. Sangma
said the country was facing "isolation" internationally and
lamented that the BJP-led coalition still has no foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Though Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee described his talks
with his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif last week in Colombo,
Sri Lanka, as "cordial and constructive", Sangma said, Sharif
dismissed the talks as a "waste of time".
</P>
<P>
Stating that India has not been able to carry conviction with
the so-called key interlocutors after the nuclear tests, Sangma
said it was due to the "inconsistency between our call for
disarmament and our nuclear tests and weaponization".
</P>
<P>
Other factors were that there was inconsistency between the
nuclear tests and the image and reality of India as a land of
poverty, malnutrition and unemployment, he said.
</P>
<P>
National security could not be preserved, protected and
enhanced due to the nuclear tests and it could not be achieved
without security in various other fields like food, job and
health, said Sangma, former speaker of the Indian Parliament.
