<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes Butler for Working in Old Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Monday criticized U.N. chief
arms inspector Richard Butler for continuing his old working style
in dealing with its weapons issues, saying the ongoing talks would
not yield good results.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Butler, Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz said he had told Butler that "I am not surprised to know that
you are still working in the same old style, though you promised
in our last meeting that the work program we agreed upon would be
honestly and swiftly implemented."
</P>
<P>
Aziz and Butler reached an agreement in June on a two-month
program of work for weapons inspections. Butler told a press
conference held after the conclusion of the agreement that the
light at the end of the tunnel for Iraq was more visible than
before.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here on Sunday for a three-day visit. He and
Aziz held the first round of talks Monday on missile warheads,
indigenous production and the biological file. They will start the
second round of talks in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The way the United Nations Special Commission, or UNSCOM,
worked last month was the same of ignoring essential issues of
disarmament while focusing on minor and insignificant issues to
waste time, prolong work and distort the picture of the situation,
Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM is charged with overseeing the elimination of Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
It must certify that Iraq has destroyed the long-range missiles
and nuclear, chemical and biological weapons before the U.N.
Security Council can lift the crippling economic sanctions imposed
on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"The manner in which UNSCOM teams worked were neither honest
nor swift. In fact they were games and maneuvers intended for
prolongation and distortion," Aziz said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
