<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets with Danish Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, met
here today with a delegation of the Foreign Affairs Committee of
the Danish Parliament led by its chairwoman, Helle Degn.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to the delegation, Li said he hoped
that the current visit would help Danish parliament members deepen
their understanding about China, and also strengthen cooperation
between the foreign affairs committees of the two parliaments.
</P>
<P>
At the request of his guests, Li introduced China's reform,
opening-up and economic construction after the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Li told guests that China's target is to build socialism with
Chinese characteristics, and China is still a developing country
in the primary stage of socialism. During the past 20 years, he
said, China has emphasized proper handling of the relationship
between reform, development and stability, which is an important
experience.
</P>
<P>
According to the spirit of the 15th CPC National Congress,
China is implementing two basic strategies of invigorating the
country through science and education and achieving sustained
development, both keys to the modernization of the country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On China's democratic system, Li said China exercises the
system of people's congresses and the system of multi-party
cooperation and political consultation under the leadership of the
CPC. China develops its own democracy and legal system according
to its specific situation, and is undertaking to build itself into
a prosperous, democratic and civilized socialist country ruled by
law, he said.
</P>
<P>
On China's foreign policy, Li said China is pursuing an
independent foreign policy of peace, and attaches great importance
to relations with Denmark and other European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
As the delegation is scheduled to tour Tibet, Li introduced in
detail the history, culture and religion of Tibet, the CPC's and the
Chinese government's policy toward the region, and its great
development since the democratic reform in 1959.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the Danish guests would have a
better understanding of Tibet and reach their conclusions through
their own experiences there.
</P>
<P>
Degn expressed her hope that cooperation between the two
parliaments and their foreign affairs committees would further
increase. She also expressed sympathy and solicitude to those
provinces suffering heavy floods, and hoped that the disaster
areas would overcome the difficulty as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
