<HEADLINE> Cohen Optimistic About Manila's Ratification of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William S.
Cohen expressed his optimism here Monday that the Philippine
Senate will ratify the Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA) as it will
help Manila and Washington work in partnership for the stability
of the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"The Visiting Forces Agreement is going to help the United
States and the Philippines work more closely together and I would
like to be clear on this point, the U.S. does not seek any bases
in the Philippines," Cohen told a press conference here after his
talks with Philippine Defense Secretary Orlando S. Mercado.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is an expanded mutual security relationship with
the Philippines. That is why our government supports the
agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen denied that his visit or that of U.S. State Secretary
Madeleine Albright last week was to pressure the Manila government
for the ratification of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Albright was here last week for the ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) Regional Forum.
</P>
<P>
The focus of talks between the defense secretaries of the two
countries was the VFA, which is pending for ratification by the
Senate in the next few weeks, according to the Philippine News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that Mercado-Cohen talks touched on many topics
such as ways in which the Philippines and the U.S. could improve
their security relations and the stability of the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the exchange of security dialogues between
Washington and most countries in Asia that includes training of
military personnel, it said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said that he discussed with his Filipino counterpart
other areas of mutual interests that include exercises, disaster
relief, and other subjects of mutual and regional interests.
</P>
<P>
"We also explored ways in which we could work together on
procurement (and) reform, something that I have been engaged on
for many years as member of the Senate," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. is sure that the Philippine Senate will
approve the VFA, Cohen said that there is a need to work hard.
</P>
<P>
"The prospects for approval are very good. But I think as a
former legislator myself, one never counts the votes until the
votes are finally in," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also cited the commitment made by the Philippine
government to work hard for the ratification of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Mercado, who in 1991 voted against the extension of the
Philippines-U.S. Military Bases Agreement (MBA), said that he is
supporting the ratification of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Mercado explained that the VFA and the MBA are not the same
because the VFA only calls for a joint exercise between Filipino
and American troops on a periodic basis.
</P>
<P>
He said that he opposed the MBA because of the permanent
stationing of U.S. troops in the country and the VFA does not.
</P>
<P>
"We feel that these exercises will be of use and beneficial to
our country, especially now we are in a bind and unable to pursue
with gusto our modernization plan," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here Sunday, also met with Philippine
President Joseph Estrada during the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
