<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film on 7 Greatest places in World to be Shown in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A film that will take the
audience to seven of the planet's most obscure and awe-inspiring
natural wonders will start screening at the Hong Kong Space Museum
here Tuesday, according to the Provisional Urban Council.
</P>
<P>
The 38-minute film, "The Greatest Places" starts off from 250
million years ago when the planet's "super continent" begins
splitting apart, unleashing massive climatic powers across the
globe which greatly affect the places to this day.
</P>
<P>
The film then tours seven diversities of the Earth, from the
isolated island of Madagascar off the coast of Africa which has
bred an exotic assortment of wildlife including two thirds of the
world's species of chameleons, to a desert of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The audience will see on the impressive dome-shaped screen how
the massive movements of the Earth's crust create the world's
largest uplifted area of Tibet of China and experience the power
of the Iguazu Falls in South America, which has a total fall width
four times that of Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
Other wonders highlighted include the Amazon River in South
America, the world's largest river in terms of water mass; the
Okavango Delta in mid-Africa, Africa's largest oasis, and
Greenland, the largest island in the world where snow falls every
month of the year, testing the limits of human existence.
</P>
<P>
"No other movie of this sort that I know of shows as many
remote worldwide locations," film director Mal Wolfe said.
</P>
<P>
The film also helps viewers explore these locations by looking
at the wildlife, culture and people that define them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
