<HEADLINE> Singapore Minister to Visit Indonesia to Present Humanitarian Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government
announced Monday Minister for Education and Second Minister for
Defense Teo Chee Hean will visit Indonesia to present humanitarian
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Teo Chee Hean will lead a delegation of senior officials to
attend a handover ceremony that will take place at Indonesia's
Halim Airport to mark the first delivery of humanitarian aid to
the country, the government said in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
Teo Chee Hean will also make a courtesy call on Indonesian
President B. j. Habibie and a number of Indonesian cabinet
members, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The aid worth 12 million Singapore dollars (7 million U.S.
dollars) was announced on July 6 by the Singapore government.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs that
day said recognizing the hardships the current economic crisis has
caused Indonesia, the Singapore government "will be extending 12
million Singapore dollars worth of humanitarian assistance in rice
and medicines to the Indonesian people to help alleviate their
difficulties."
</P>
<P>
The statement also noted that the amount "is in addition to the
5 million Singapore dollars in humanitarian aid that the Singapore
Red Cross has announced."
</P>
<P>
After nearly a month of close consultation, officials from both
sides have worked out the details for the handover of the aid.
</P>
<P>
Under the handover plan, the aid will be delivered in three
separate shipments over the next few weeks. The first phase will
comprise 10,000 tons of rice and a supply of medicines and
subsequent shipments of aid will follow in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Navy and Air Force of Singapore will transport the aid
cargo to Indonesia by sea and air while the Indonesian armed
forces will assist in distribution of the rice and medicine to the
needy areas in Sumatra and Java, Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
