<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Warn Use of Vitamins in Fight Against Heart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Vitamins could cause more harm
than good in the fight against heart disease, world leaders in
cardiac research said Monday in western Australia's coastal city
of Perth.
</P>
<P>
The warning came as cardiologists predicted developing nations
would be hardest hit as heart disease became the world's biggest
killer in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
David Harrison, a U.S. heart disease prevention expert, warned
vitamins, known as anti-oxidants and hailed in recent years as the
ultimate in heart disease prevention, could actually help cause
heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
"Stop taking anti-oxidant vitamins until there is much better
research. At least until current studies are completed in about
two years," Harrison, a globally recognized cardiologist, was
quoted Monday by the Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vitamins A, C and E have been sold by the medical community as
substances which eradicate harmful free radicals - highly active
cells which can inflame artery walls and promote cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
Harrison said there was still much research to be done on
anti-oxidant vitamins, but current results suggested after they
"scavenged" free radicals, anti-oxidants themselves could become
free radicals.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know for sure that anti-oxidants are good, if they
are bad, or if they have no effect at all," he told the Cardiac
Society of Australia and New Zealand's annual conference in Perth.
</P>
<P>
Naturally occurring anti-oxidants in fruit and vegetables were
the safe alternative to highly-concentrated vitamin pills,
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
The health message came as world-renowned Canadian cardiologist
Salam Yusuf predicted by 2020, 75-80 percent of all heart attacks
and strokes would occur in third world nations.
</P>
<P>
"It is entirely lifestyle changes and environmental changes now
occurring in the developing countries, including increased use of
tobacco, increased urbanization with its stresses, increased
consumption of the wrong foods, decreased energy loss," he said.
</P>
<P>
An ever-intensifying push by tobacco companies in developing
nations could mean heart disease will increase far beyond Yusuf's
predictions.
</P>
<P>
"The single most important thing we can do in terms of
prevention of heart disease is tobacco control," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to better education about the risks of cigarette smoking
and the importance of a balanced diet, developed nations could
expect to see a continued decrease in heart disease deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Mercenaries Join Angola Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A mercenary force of more
than 300 men, among them many South Africans, is joining the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in their
fight against government troops, local intelligence sources have
revealed.
</P>
<P>
The Star paper Monday quoted unidentified intelligence sources
as saying that most of those signed up are former members of the
military advisory organization of Executive Outcomes, who were
previously active in Angola and other African states as well as
in the Middle East and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Executive Outcomes, well-known for its mercenary business
abroad in the past, said last year it had closed down its
military operations ahead of new legislation passed by parliament
this year, which prohibits South Africans from offering freelance
military skills and services to foreign countries and companies.
</P>
<P>
The legislation makes provision for heavy fines, confiscation
of property and long prison sentences for mercenaries convicted
by local courts.
</P>
<P>
The South African government was reportedly aware of South
African mercenaries inside Angola. Last week, Defense Minister
Joe Modise said action would have to be taken to prevent South
African mercenaries and supplies reaching the UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the tense situation in Angola, Modise said: "We
will have to stop the trafficking of weapons and supplies to the
warring parties. There are rumours that supplies are coming from
this country and that our people are involved."
</P>
<P>
The mercenaries were reportedly signed up by a new, so far
unnamed security group with links to business interests in South
Africa, the United States, France and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
