<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Media Taking Watchdog Role in Courts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Live coverage of trials, a new
but popular practice in China, has enabled more Chinese to observe
and supervise the process of courtroom hearings which had been
secretive until only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
Experts here pointed out that broadcasting trials live not only
provides the general public with a chance to supervise the
judicial departments, but also facilitates China's judges to
improve their professional skills.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People's Court, expressed a
positive attitude toward the practice, saying that as long as the
media respects the facts and takes an impartial stand, live
coverage of trials is always welcome.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 40 television stations across China have had
live court coverage, the first of which is the Nanjing City
Television Station in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Since April 1, 1994, the station began the practice of live
coverage in a weekly program titled "Courtroom Fax" and, to date,
the program has shown more than 200 trials.
</P>
<P>
On July 11, 1998, China Central Television (CCTV), the
country's state-run television station, broadcast a courtroom
hearing live nationwide for the first time, which has sparked a
reaction among ordinary Chinese.
</P>
<P>
A number of television stations in China are reportedly
planning live court coverage as part of an effort to catch up with
their coastal counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"The primary objective of live coverage is to improve the legal
awareness of the general public," said an official in Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing City Television Station explicitly stipulates
that live broadcasting gives priority to those civil, economic and
administrative cases which the ordinary citizens care about most,
provided that those cases do not involve national security,
individuals' privacy or juvenile delinquents.
</P>
<P>
While experts and lawyers are invited to comment on the trials
being broadcast alive, hot lines are also prepared for the
audiences to air their opinions, the official said.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in Nanjing, capital of Jiangsu Province,
shows that many local residents have an enormous interest in the
program and frequently ask their friends to record the program
when they can't afford the time to watch the trials.
</P>
<P>
"The objectivity of live coverage helps it win popularity,"
said Zhang Guoliang, director of the Social Education Department
of the station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
