Sunday for Lin Ti-chuan, a Taiwanese who died recently in
Haicheng, a city in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Lin's parents, relatives and close friends came here on Sunday
to handle the funeral affairs. Lin died after she was reportedly
kidnapped and illegally detained because of an economic dispute.
</P>
<P>
The local government helped arrange a memorial hall for
Lin. The relevant departments, including the associations of
Taiwan-funded enterprises of Dalian and Haicheng cities as well as
the Liaoning Provincial Federation of Taiwan Compatriots,
presented flower baskets and elegiac couplets.
</P>
<P>
Lin's picture was hung in the center of a wall covered by lily
flowers. Fresh flowers and fruit were placed before her picture.
</P>
<P>
Before going to the memorial hall, a Master of the Law who came
specially from Taiwan carried out rituals for Ms. Lin at the place
where she was illegally detained, according to Taiwan's customs.
</P>
<P>
Upon leaving the memorial hall after the memorial service,
Lin's parents requested the incense in the hall be kept burning
until they left Haicheng. Local officials promised to fulfill
their wish since the people on both sides of the Taiwan Straits
are linked each other by flesh and blood.
</P>
<P>
Lin's father expressed his gratitude to the local government
for its support and help in handling the funeral affairs. 
</P>
