<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half-Year Crime Rate Up in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by the
police Monday showed the crime rate went up by 4.7 percent in
Singapore for the first half of this year with an across-the-board
increase in crime figures.
</P>
<P>
The statistics came after Minister for Home Affairs Wong Kan
Seng revealed at a general meeting of the National Crime
Prevention Council Friday that 23,844 crime cases were recorded in
the first half of this year, 1,073 more than the 22,811 in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, the highest increase was recorded
for crimes such as snatch theft, car theft and motor vehicle
break-ins.
</P>
<P>
Cases of snatch theft was a jump of more than 55 percent, while
car theft and motor vehicle break-ins increased by more than 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Murder cases, rape, housebreaking and robberies also increased,
registering 12 more murder cases against the same period last
year, a 30 percent increase in rape cases and a marginal rise in
housebreaking and robbery cases.
</P>
<P>
However, there was an almost 12 percent drop in rioting, and a
decrease in the number of outrage of modesty cases.
</P>
<P>
At Friday's meeting Wong Kan Seng said "although the overall
figure is no cause for alarm, we are still concerned."
</P>
<P>
"The police have spared no effort in combating crime, but the
public must continue to do their part as well," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of Police Khoo Boon Hui said on another occasion
that the police have focused their efforts on those crimes that
have increased significantly and on arresting serial offenders in
order to better tackle the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
