<HEADLINE> New Technology Developed to Recreate Crime Scenes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- In what Australian police
claimed to be a world first, visual crime scenes will be recreated
in the courtroom following computer technology developments by
police experts in Australia's Queensland state.
</P>
<P>
They have developed a way to allow judges, jurors and witnesses
to "walk through a crime scene" and examine fingerprints and
forensic evidence, without setting foot in the real-life site.
</P>
<P>
The new technology, Interactive Crime Scene Recording System,
digitally combines the hundreds of photographs taken at a crime
scene to create a 360 degree view of the area, allowing it to be
examined from any angle.
</P>
<P>
"As far as I'm aware, we're the only police service in the
world to have taken this (system) on board," Acting Deputy
Commissioner Ron McGibbon told the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
The technology had the potential to cut back the crime scene
paperwork swamping courtrooms, and present the same information in
a simple and compact computer presentation.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it will revolutionize the way we introduce evidence
in court," said Senior Sergeant Adrian Freeman, one of the
system's designers.
</P>
<P>
The system, developed over two years, has been demonstrated
successfully overseas and "is rapidly being adopted as an industry
standard", he said.
</P>
<P>
The trial period will continue for another year, "until we are
sure it is tamper-proof", McGibbon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
