<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malnutrition to Cause 22.9B-Dollar Productivity Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will lose 22.9 billion
U.S. dollars in productivity in ten years to come if the present
state of malnutrition among children and mothers continues, a
press report said Monday quoting a Health Ministry document.
</P>
<P>
The country will lose 11.4 billion dollars in productivity due
to "stunting" caused by protein deficiency, 6.8 billion dollars
due to anemia and iron deficiency among mothers and 4.7 billion
dollars due to iodine deficiency among both, the document
elaborated.
</P>
<P>
The "unacceptably high rate of malnutrition in the country is
one of the highest in the world which is reducing the country's
development potential, it said.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of the babies are born underweight and 51
percent of the children suffer from "under-height for age" due to
"stunting" caused by malnutrition, it stated.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of pregnant women are still anemic, it
noted, adding it is estimated that about 600 children die every
day due to malnutrition and 25 percent of maternal deaths are
related to hemorrhage and anemia, it added.
</P>
<P>
Stunting significantly affects children's physical and mental
capacity and their productivity when they become adults, said an
expert.
</P>
<P>
"Undernourishment leads to many diseases. Indirectly,
malnutrition is the biggest killer of human beings in Bangladesh,"
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Overall prevalence of malnutrition in childhood remained at 91
percent" in Bangladesh, said a World Bank review completed last
June. It further said that night blindness among children over
five and pregnant and lactating women increased to over three
percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 56.3 percent of babies in the age group of six months to
six years were "moderate to severely stunted" in the country,
according to a 1996 child nutrition survey.
</P>
<P>
"Nutrition received little attention in national development
till recent days," the report quoted an official of the Health
Ministry as saying. "The government allocated very limited funds
for nutrition."
</P>
<P>
The government has prepared a ten-year program with a cost of
one billion dollars to reduce malnutrition to the extent that it
does not cause a public health problem. The program covering the
entire country, now under negotiation with the World Bank, is
expected to be started from July 2000, according to the document.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
