<HEADLINE> Yellow River Enters Main Flood Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Efforts to battle flooding
along the Yellow River, China's second longest river following the
Yangtze, have entered a crucial stage with the rapid approach of
the main flood season.
</P>
<P>
Records show that most floods occur in late July and early
August, and rainfall in the upper and middle reaches of the river
is expected to be higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
"We must closely monitor the flood situation and must not relax
our vigilance for even a single day," said Zhuang Jinglin, an
official with the Yellow River Water Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
Provinces along the Yellow River have mobilized a 2.5 million
task force fully prepared to battle summer flooding, with ample
stockpiles of flood control materials
</P>
<P>
The first Yellow River flood crest entered the Bohai Sea on
August 1, with the Huayuankou Hydrological Stations recording a
normal water flow rate of 4,000 cu.m/second.
</P>
<P>
Yellow River flooding on the scale witnessed along the Yangtze
River this year will create an extremely grave situation since
many sections of the riverbed rise some 6-10 meters above the
surrounding ground level, according to Zhuang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
