<HEADLINE> Fire Dies Out at Israeli Toxic Waste Dump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The largest ever fire at the
national hazardous waste dump in southern Israel died out
Monday morning, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that bulldozers had began to clear up the site,
which is near the southern city of Beersheva in the Negev Desert.
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out Sunday evening after vats storing used
lithium batteries apparently caught fire due to hot weather.
</P>
<P>
Lithium is not defined as poisonous, but is highly flammable
and explosive, and neither water nor foam can be used to put out
the fire.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters, who rushed to the scene, fought the
conflagration for some five hours and finally decided to let the
main flashpoint burn itself out. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
The site serves as the country's main dump for hazardous
waste. Thousands of barrels, which are stacked across a large open
area, contain as much as 60,000 tonnes of dangerous materials.
</P>
<P>
The environment activist group Greenpeace's representative in
Israel Ofer Ben Dov has called for investigation into the
incident.
</P>
<P>
He said the government must regard the site as a national
priority and take steps to make it safer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
