<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Fall due to Weaker Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed more than one percent weaker Monday due to a slump in Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index shed 30.8 points, or 1.14
percent, to close at a low for the day of 2,673.8.
</P>
<P>
"At about two o'clock our market began to fall away quite
steeply," Macquarie Equities client adviser Rob Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
"The very weak Asian markets drove us down," he commented.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the key Nikkei stock average closed down 213.89
points, or 1.31 percent, at 16,165.08.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian markets, the all industrials index plunged
54.8 points to 4,723.0, while 11.3 points were clipped from the
all resources index which closed at 1,015.9.
</P>
<P>
Diversified miners BHP and Rio Tinto were the only mining
majors to remain in positive territory after an overnight slump in
metals prices.
</P>
<P>
BHP ended the day half-a-cent up at 13.36 Australian dollars,
off an intra-day high of 13.70 Australian dollar, after the
much-anticipated announcement that National Australia Bank
Managing Director Don Argus would succeed Jerry Ellis as BHP
chairman next year.
</P>
<P>
Traders said investors welcomed the news of the BHP changes.
</P>
<P>
Rio picked up 20 cents to 18.22 Australian dollars, amid
reports that the Ango-Australian mining giant could be eyeing
BHP's minerals division.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 26 points to 1,026.9 in line with a
weakening of the precious metal price.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney was 286.55 U.S.
dollars an ounce in afternoon trade, compared with 289.65 U.S.
dollars an ounce Friday.
</P>
<P>
The banking index slid 68.3 to 5,967.3 points, with Australia's
four biggest banks losing ground.
</P>
<P>
National Australia slipped 38 cents to 22.54 Australian
dollars, the Commonwealth Bank of Australia tumbled 23 cents to
20.32 Australian dollars, and Westpac and ANZ banks both dropped
four cents to 10.37 Australian dollars and 10.63 Australian
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
A bank holiday in Sydney dampened volume, with national
turnover for the day at 209.91 million shares changing hands for
296.49 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Falling stocks outnumbered rising stocks, 749 to 339. 
</P>
