<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Commission Automated Customs System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will commission its
Automated System for Customs Data (ASYCUDA) by the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Samuel Ango, the Sole Administrator of the
Nigeria Customs Service, said all the customs commands in the
Lagos and eastern area will be connected to the system in the
first phase, while other commands would follow, the Daily Times
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
ASYCUDA is a computerized system for processing customs
declarations aimed at increasing efficiency, minimizing the risk
of fraud and maximizing revenue receipts for government.
</P>
<P>
The system is now being used in more than 70 customs
administrations worldwide while 12 out of the 16 member countries
of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
currently use the software for their customs clearing procedures,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigeria ASYCUDA system was initiated in February this year
and is being handled by the ECOWAS Community Computer Center, the
newspaper said. 
