<HEADLINE> India Says It Respects Nuclear Free Status in SE Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee assured members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) Monday that his country respected the status
of the nuclear weapons free zone in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee declared in the Parliament that New Delhi committed
itself to a comprehensive and non-discriminatory global nuclear
disarmament regime.
</P>
<P>
India, according to the prime minister, set at rest
misconceptions about its nuclear tests in May at the recent ASEAN
conferences in Manila and during his interaction with leaders of
member countries of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) in Colombo last week.
</P>
<P>
"Our initiatives for confidence building and disarmament have
been appreciated," Vajpayee declared, adding that "there was
agreement on the need to commence purposeful negotiations towards
a comprehensive and non-discriminatory global nuclear disarmament
regime and a nuclear weapon-free world".
</P>
<P>
He said that India's participation in the ASEAN and ASEAN
Regional Forum meetings last month was particularly important as
it provided an opportunity to clarify New Delhi's policy on
nuclear disarmament in the context of its nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee declared that India was ready to enter into bilateral
free trade arrangements with interested SAARC countries, adding
that India had decided to substantially increase the ceiling for
investment in SAARC countries from 8 million to 15 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decision would encourage a greater flow of Indian
investment and stimulate trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka had taken up India's offer on bilateral free trade
purposefully towards setting up a free trade area and a group of
experts would be set up to negotiate a comprehensive legal
framework for liberalized trade and facilitation measures, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On relations with neighboring Pakistan, the Indian prime
minister said he looked forward to continuing a "purposeful"
interaction with his counterpart Nawaz Sharif, asserting that all
outstanding issues, including Jammu and Kashmir, should be
addressed through a "direct, composite dialogue".
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers held talks on July 29 on the sidelines
of the 10th SAARC summit.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Vajpayee said, he reiterated India's
commitment to developing peaceful and friendly ties with Pakistan
and New Delhi's interest in a "secure, stable and prosperous
Pakistan". 
</P>
