<HEADLINE> Water Level on Yangtze's Upper Reaches Still Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The water level on the upper
reaches of the Yangtze River is continuing to rise because of more
rainfall in the past few days, putting heavy pressure on the
river's middle and lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
High water recorded at the Cuntan Hydrological Station by 8
a.m. (Beijing time) today rose to 176.08 meters with a water flow
of 37,500 cubic meters per second, according to reports of the
State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Another flood crest is expected to reach the Cuntan
Hydrological Station at a flow of 44,000 cubic meters per second
by 5 a.m. Tuesday. The crest is expected to pass Yichang City in
Hubei Province by 8 p.m. on Aug. 5 at a flow of 48,000 cubic
meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Flooding on the Yangtze River is reaching another critical
moment, officials said, as many of the river's dikes have been
soaked in high water for four days.
</P>
<P>
However, the water level at the section between Shishou and
Luoshan is declining at a daily rate of two centimeters to two
decimeters. At 8 this morning, the water level fell to 35.03
meters at Lianhua Pond and to 34.22 meters at the Luohe
Hydrological Station, both still above the danger mark.
</P>
<P>
The water level dropped to 35.2 meters at Dongting Lake this
morning, 0.22 meters lower than Sunday's level; and to 22.51
meters at Poyang Lake, 0.4 centimeters lower than Sunday's level.
</P>
<P>
The flood peak at the Nengjiang River in northeast China is
reportedly moving downstream. The water level at the Dalai
Hydrological Station in Jilin province was at 130.08 meters by 5
a.m. today at a flow of 7,630 cubic meters per second, 0.4 meters
above the safe level.
</P>
<P>
Water experts predicted that both the water level and flow at
the Dalai Hydrological Station will surpass previous records when
the flood crest reaches there either Tuesday or Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
