<HEADLINE> Japan's Foreign Reserves Up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan's foreign exchange reserves
rose by 1,624 million U.S. dollars in July from the previous month
to 207,498 million dollars, the Finance Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The increase follows June's fall of 1,101 million dollars,
which was the first decline since April and the result of
dollar-selling intervention by the Japanese monetary authorities
to prop up the falling yen.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been the largest foreign-reserve holder in the world
for the 57th consecutive month in July.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves consist of convertible foreign currencies,
gold and International Monetary Fund special drawing rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
