<HEADLINE> 2,134 People Killed in July Tsunami in PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea's Prime
Minister Bill Skate said here Monday that the official death toll
was 2,134, with 9,483 people homeless and 628 in hospitals caused
by the tsunami tragedy on the evening of July 17.
</P>
<P>
Skate, who is here to express gratitude to the Australian
government and people for their assistance, told reporters at a
press conference that "it was wonderful to know that the
Australians flew in quickly, they were the first to land there".
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Australian Prime Minister John Howard
told his guest that "we will provide whatever extra is needed to
ensure two or three new schools, some facilities that are more
accessible for people who've been disabled as a result of the
tragedy, medical support for those with orthopedic injuries and
amputations."
</P>
<P>
Howard also promised support to rebuild the local economy and
earthquake monitoring to prevent a repeat of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Howard said Australia would be giving an additional 1 million
Australian dollars (0.62 million U.S. dollars) in aid, on top of
the 2 million Australian dollars already spent on the disaster.
</P>
<P>
He said the tragedy had provided an opportunity for Australians
to put that commitment into action through the Australian Defense
Force medical teams who were operating in the disaster area within
days of the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
