<HEADLINE> Dollar Climbs 145 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar climbed to 145.71 yen
in Tokyo Monday for the fist time since June 16, the day before the
United States and Japan jointly intervened on the foreign exchange
market to prop up the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 145.63-65 yen at 5 p.m. (local time), up
from 144.79-82 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, and from 144.70-80 yen late
Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the U.S. currency weakened to 144.60 yen before
resuming its upward trek, pushed by market players anxious for the
Japanese government to get to work on improving its economy.
</P>
<P>
Pessimism about the ability of the new Japanese government to pull
Japan out of its current recession is weighing on the yen, dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet of Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, installed last
Thursday, has a record low 31.9 percent approval rating, according to
a Kyodo News opinion poll released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Market players are likely to test the year's high of 146.75 yen,
also seen in Tokyo on June 16, because they lack reasons to hold on to
the Japanese currency, dealers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
