<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks fell 383.43
points, or 4.83 percent, to close at 7,552.77 on Monday because of
concerns over the renewed weakness of the Japanese yen and the
local economy.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng index lost 201.57 points, or 2.54 percent, to
hit 7,734.63 in the first two minutes of trading, and finished
morning trading 378.66 points, or 4.77 percent, lower at 7,557.54.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said trading was volatile "out of a combination
external and internal factors."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen was traded in Tokyo at a low of 145 against
the U.S. dollar, triggering losses on Hong Kong market and other
regional bourses Monday.
</P>
<P>
There were also concerns over the local economy as the Hong
Kong government prepared to reveal GDP growth rate for the first
quarter, and Hang Seng Index heavyweight HSBC banking group
announced interim results, said dealers. Both announcements were
arranged shortly after the market close.
</P>
<P>
The government just announced that the first-quarter GDP fell
by 2.8 percent in real terms over a year earlier, the worst in a
decade, as the economy absorbed the impact of the regional
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
All the four sub indices of the index recorded heavy losses
Monday, out of which property shares lost 547 points or 6.7
percent and finance shares shedding 608 points, or close to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Turnover increased to 4,743 million HK dollars (608 million
U.S. dollars). 
