<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK GDP Falls 2.8 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's gross domestic
product (GDP) shrank by 2.8 percent in real terms in the first
quarter of 1998 from a year earlier, the government said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figure, the worst in more than a decade, represented a
further deceleration from the 2.7 percent growth in the fourth
quarter of 1997, according to the Census and Statistics
Department.
</P>
<P>
The department in a statement attributed the slump to "a
significant slowdown in domestic demand, as the economy absorbed
the impact of the regional financial turmoil."
</P>
<P>
"A more moderate export performance and continued weakness in
inbound tourism also contributed" to the GDP slump.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary data had put the contraction at around 2 percent
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest GDP figures, Government Economist Tang
Kwong-yiu said: "The weak economic performance in the first
quarter of 1998 reflects a continuing consolidation and adaptation
process, as the economy weathers the impact of the regional
financial turmoil."
</P>
<P>
"As an integral part of the regional economy, our economy
cannot be immune from the profound shocks emanating elsewhere in
the region which are beyond our control," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, our economy has been adjusting expeditiously so
as to recoup competitiveness," said Tang, adding property prices
and rentals have fallen substantially, while wages and salaries
are softening.
</P>
<P>
He observed: "As the adjustment is gone through, it will
provide us with a strong basis for a prompt return to growth when
the regional environment and the economic outlook for Hong Kong
improve." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Advance on Opposition Headquarters in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
militia Monday closed in on Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the
rival northern alliance, after capturing a strategic town in
northern Afghanistan, reports monitored here said.
</P>
<P>
The student militia forces were advancing from the west and
east of Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of the Afghan capital
of Kabul, in Balkh province, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Mazar-e-Sharif is the only major Afghan city not under the
strict Islamic rule of the Taliban, who now control more than
two-thirds of the country's territory.
</P>
<P>
Some local commanders in the key district of Balkh, only 20 km
west of Mazar-e-Sharif, have joined the Taliban forces, the
reports added.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's new assault followed their capture of Sheberghan,
provincial capital of Jowzjan province and around 120 km west of
Mazar-e-Sharif Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sheberghan was the native stronghold of warlord Rashid Dostum,
one of the strongmen in the Mazar-e-Sharif-based anti-Taliban
alliance, which groups forces led by Dostum, former Afghan
military chief Ahmad Masood and Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat leader Karim
Khalili.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's mouthpiece Radio Shariat earlier announced that the
recent gains had placed their forces "on the threshold of victory"
in their aim to capture the remaining one-third of Afghanistan
held now by the northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
The militia had briefly held Mazar-e-Sharif in May last year
but were forced out with heavy casualties after an opposition
commander who helped them suddenly changed sides again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
