<HEADLINE> Taliban Deny Crash of Their Transport Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
militia Monday contradicted the news report that one of their
transport planes had crashed during a routine flight to frontlines
in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We have checked in that area (Kunduz province) and found no
such incident happened," said Abdul Hayee Motamin, Taliban's s
spokesman in the southern stronghold of Kandahar, when contacted
by telephone.
</P>
<P>
"This report was released last night from Kabul, but there is
no truth in it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, reports reaching here from Kabul quoted Taliban's
mouthpiece Radio Shariat as saying that an aged Soviet-made
Antonov 32 belonging to the militia had crashed due to technical
problems while approaching for landing at their northern enclave
of Kunduz province. 
</P>
