<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell sharply in Tokyo
Monday on weak yen and renewed fears over Japan's fragile
financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange nosedived 213.89 points, or
1.31 percent, from last Friday's close to end at 16,165.08.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 16.80 points or 1.33 percent to
1,245.24.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to an estimated 300
million shares from 379.36 million shares Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was Monday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Investors were bearish from beginning to end, with falling
Nikkei 225 futures prices in Osaka and Singapore and the drop in
the Dow Jones Industrial Average to below 8,900 Friday in New York
weighing heavily on stocks.
</P>
<P>
Banks fell hard after the Financial Supervisory Agency (FSA)
issued warnings Friday to get their act together.
</P>
<P>
Traders admitted the FSA's upcoming reports of its current
audit of major banks had investors worried.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen's fall to the 145 yen line against the
U.S. dollar in Tokyo also hurts banks. A weaker yen boosts the
value of a bank's overseas assets and lowers its capital-adequacy
ratio.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,334 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outpaced gainers 823 to 274, with 170 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
