<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, PNG Sign MOU Over Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A memorandum of understanding
(MOU) between Australia and Papua New Guinea (PNG) was signed here
Monday to lay a 1.86-billion-U.S.-dollar gas pipeline linking the
Australian state of Queensland with PNG.
</P>
<P>
Visiting PNG Prime Minister Bill Skate, who witnessed the
signing in Canberra, said the pipeline would be laid across Torres
Strait, which separated the two countries, to the rich gasfields
in PNG's southern highlands.
</P>
<P>
"At the Australian end it is intended to power an aluminum
processing plant at Gladstone (of Queensland) and an electricity
station in Townsville (of Queensland)," he told a joint news
conference after the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A consortium of companies led by Chevron is planning to develop
gas production in the southern highlands, then pipe it to Torres
Strait where the gas will be processed and the liquid petroleum
gas and condensate will be extracted.
</P>
<P>
A pipeline across Torres Strait and down the Cape York
Peninsula, the nearest part of continental Australia to PNG, will
then carry the gas to a proposed a 300-million-U.S.-dollar power
station in the coastal city of Townsville and Comalco company's
proposed a 868-million-U.S.-dollar alumina refinery at Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
Gladstone is a coastal town about 1,500 km southeast of the
Cape York Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
PNG Minister for Petroleum and Energy Rabbie Namaliu and
Australian Resources and Energy Minister Warwick Parer signed the
memorandum.
</P>
<P>
Parer said the pipeline could also supply cities in Queensland
such as Bowen, Mackay and Cairns, and mining communities such as
Weipa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
