<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August (Xinhua) -- Share Prices ended higher on
Singapore Market Monday although external worries continued
dampening sentiment on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index (STII) gained
10.56 points to close at 1,074.76 points and the gains were
largely achieved on buying index-linked stocks.
</P>
<P>
The turnover totaled 91.71 million shares worth 133.25 million
Singapore dollars (about 77.02 million U.S. dollars). There were
198 losers against 73 gainers while 316 counters remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
TAC 200 was the most active stock as it finished on a turnover
of 6.37 million units. It was followed by Li Xin that had 5.49
million counters done. SingTel was next with 4.15 million shares
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 was the top gainer of the day as it gained 60 cents
to close at 21.60 Singapore dollars. UOB F edged up 19 cents to
5.15 Singapore dollars at close. KepFELS was up 16 cents to finish
at 3.38 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Sime Uep was the biggest loser as it lost 2.62
Singapore dollars to close at 0.78 Singapore dollars. RothmansI
shed 30 cents to end at 7.70 Singapore dollars. Venture inched
down 26 cents to finish at 4.16 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
As most Singapore-listed companies report their half year or
full year results this month or next, focus on the stock market
has been shifted on corporate results.
</P>
<P>
Investors are worried that companies may report poor financial
results as a result of the regional economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
However, a better than expected profit declared Friday by UOB
led to some picking of banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the broader market was still bearish amid Japanese
yen weakness and a slide in regional bourses.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the yen fell through the 145 level Monday
against the U.S. dollar amid persistent worries about the Japanese
economy, that has kept many investors sidelined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
