<HEADLINE> Efforts Expected from Japan's New Cabinet to Restore Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China,
expressed the hope here today that the new Japanese cabinet led by
Prime Minister Obuchi Keizo would made new efforts to invigorate
the Japanese economy and advance Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
China's economy is confronted with some problems due to the
pressure of the Southeast Asian financial crisis, and China needs
an improving exterior environment while depending on its own
efforts to tackle the difficulties, Li told a presidents'
delegation with Hitachi Ltd. of Japan.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that Japan, as China's largest trade partner,
will initiate effective financial and economic policies to
resurrect its economy, since doing so would help ease and overcome
the crisis, Li said.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 20th anniversary of the China-Japan Peace
and Friendship Treaty, Li said, expressing his hope that both
sides would seize this opportunity to promote the healthy and
stable growth of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Li recalled his past contacts with Hitachi, including his visit
to its headquarters in 1979 and his meeting with Hitachi's former
president during last year's Japan tour, and said he hoped the
company would further expand its cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Head of the delegation Kanai Tsutomu, president and
representative-director of Hitachi, said that relations between
Japan and China have entered a new development stage, and Hitachi
is willing to make its due efforts to strengthen bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi has conducted many cooperative projects in China, and
is willing to redefine its cooperative sphere to match China's
industrial development priority, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi also plans to increase coordination with the Chinese in
such basic industries as energy, environmental protection and
high-tech. The company is also willing to help restore Japan's
economy and ease the pressure on China caused by the financial
crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi is one of the first groups of big Japanese companies to
enter the Chinese market, and has so far opened more than 50
jointly financed or cooperative enterprises throughout the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
