<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forecast for Israel's 1998 Economic Growth Gloomy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel's economic growth in
1998 could slide to 1.1 percent from last year's 1.9 percent, an
economic forecast published by the Manufacturers Association of
Israel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast, which is in line with other recent predictions,
suggested another gloomy year for Israeli economy which has begun
to slow down since 1996 after a decade of rapid expansion.
</P>
<P>
"The year of 1998 will go down in memory as one of the Israeli
economy's worst years, and the country's industrial growth is
likely to reach only 1.7 percent in 1998, just under the 1.8
percent posted in 1997," the report said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, the unemployment rate in Israel was
expected to rise to 10.4 percent, and the average rate of
unemployment for the whole year would reach 9.3 percent, a record
high in five years, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The association estimated that the business output would
increase by only 0.3 percent in 1998, the lowest rate since
1976. Overall investement in 1998 would drop by 4.5 percent from
that in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The one bright spot, the forecast said, would be the continuing
decline of the deficit in the balance of payments, which was
expected to be reduced to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars from 3.2
billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, according to Israel's Income Tax
Commission's data, the crisis in Israel's real estate market is
deepening in 1998. A sharp 12 percent drop in the number of real
estate deals has been recorded since the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
From January to July this year, only 72,000 real estate
transactions were conducted, compared to 82,000 in the same period
of 1997, and 96,000 in the same period of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Urged to Develop Poor Southeastern Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has urged
Turkey to take systematic and effective steps to develop its poor
southeastern region, the English Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Frederich Temple, WB's representative in Turkey, said the
underdeveloped southeastern areas could become a major bottleneck
for Turkey's economy if the problems there remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
"Western and northwestern Turkey have shown a significant
development, while the east and southeast regions are extremely
poor," Temple said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the economic backwardness in the southeast to
unjust distribution of resoruces and unstable situation there due
to the constant clashes between government troops and the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been fighting for an independent
Kurdish state since 1984.
</P>
<P>
"The present Southeastern Anatolia Project has vital importance
for people living in that region. This project will contribute
to the private sector and promote new investments," Temple said.
</P>
<P>
The WB has agreed to provide necessary financial support to
the project, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the WB official said Turkey's high inflation arising
from inconsistent budget and structural problem is still among the
urgent problems needed to be tackled.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's high inflation rate, which stood at 80 percent at the
end of June, and the sharp devaluation of Turkish Lira have posed
grave threats to the country's economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Temple said that effective measures must be taken to bring down
the high inflation to create a healthy developing environment for
Turkey's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
