<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Suggests Construction of Flood Diversion Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- An expert from the Yangtze River
Flood Control Commission has suggested that China step up
construction of flood diversion areas to minimize losses caused by
floods.
</P>
<P>
"The loss will be less if we divert floods in a planned way
when the situation becomes an emergency," said Wu Daoxi, an
official from the commission.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the diversion projects along the Jingjiang River and
near Dongting Lake in the middle Yangtze Valleys have contributed
to controlling floodwaters. He added that facilities in some other
parts of the Yangtze are still substandard.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province, for example, has abandoned 11 small dikes to
divert floodwaters and lower the water level in the main stream of the
Yangtze River. Though causing more than 400 million yuan in
losses, the strategy helped protect Wuhan, an industrial and
densely populated city in the province.
</P>
<P>
Tan Qifu, another expert from the same commission, also
suggested building more reservoirs to store floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 1,000 reservoirs have been built
along the Yangtze, mostly on the middle and lower reaches of the
river. 
</P>
</TEXT>
