<HEADLINE> East, Southern Africa to Form Cruise Marketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A regional association to market
eastern and southern Africa as cruise destinations is to be
formed in October.
</P>
<P>
The 18-member state Port Management Association of Eastern and
Southern Africa (PMAESA) has approved plans to launch the
association at its recent annual meeting in Reunion, the East
African weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ports in the region could gain substantially from an
increase in cruise ships, Danielle le Normand, the assistant
manager of Reunion port, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The region has experienced a steady but slow growth in cruise
ships, especially since the opening of South Africa to the world
market.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly feel that with an aggressive marketing campaign,
both at the national and regional level, our share of the market
could be substantially increased," she said.
</P>
<P>
Reunion received 50,000 tourists last year, 9,000 of them were
on cruises.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and Mauritius receive respectively an average of 58 and
16 percent of ships in the region, followed by Seychelles. All
the three countries have seen a steady growth in cruising
industry over recent years.
</P>
<P>
However, Reunion, Mauritius and South Africa are the only
member states with modern dedicated passenger terminals. Similar
facilities are also planned for Seychelles and Kenya, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The planned association wo%lM=b%9V*A:%QP"U %IU%M5RI=5=QIf"=R=%\Q1ejIVQ" eas
tern Indian Ocean seaboard,
said Normand.
</P>
<P>
The PMAESA urged its member states to streamline and minimize
formalities in order to provide uniform treatment to cruise
vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
