<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 64,000 Angolans Flee UNITA Military Draft Tactics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of Angolans fleeing
into Zambia from forced conscriptions by Angola's opposition
UNITA movement has swelled to 64,000.
</P>
<P>
Ngande Mwanajiti, Executive Director of Inter-African Network
for Human Rights and Development, and Alex Vines, a Human Rights
Watch researcher, said here Sunday that the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has resolved to forcibly
draft into their army men and women ranging from 13 to 30 years,
Times of Zambia reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mwanajiti and Vines, who have just completed a joint field
mission to the Angolan-Zambian border and refugee camps in
Zambia, also disclosed that UNITA, in their quest to amass a
powerful battalion to topple the Angolan government, has resorted
to killing hundreds of people opposed to its ideologies.
</P>
<P>
Angola is again at the convulsion of a fresh civil war and
the number of Angolan refugees seeking asylum in Zambia will
increase to more than 80,000 by the end of the year, they said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia will soon be flooded by an influx of Angolan refugees
with thousands of them now being crossing into the country for
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the conscription for men, Vines said, women are
being forced to marry to and carry bullets for UNITA soldiers
before being educated on the use of military weapons.
</P>
<P>
The two human rights observers urged the southern African
governments to find a permanent solution to the Angolan conflict
to abate further human life loss and displacement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
