<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Port City To Upgrade Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Ningbo, a major port city in east
China's Zhejiang Province, plans to spend 10 billion yuan (1.2
billion US dollars) on communications over the next five years,
according to Li Kuiming, director of the municipal commission in
charge of the sector.
</P>
<P>
The funds will come partly from both central and local
governments, he said, noting that individuals at home and overseas
are welcome to invest in the program.
</P>
<P>
Under the government plan, the port of Ningbo will increase its
annual container handling capacity to one million TEUs by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The project also includes the extension of Lishe Airport to
raise its yearly capacity to 3.8 million passengers and 50,000
tons of cargo, the rebuilding of a railway between Ningbo and
Xiaoshan cities, and the extension of local highway network.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, the city is expected to have a
modern communications system with the port at the core, said the
director.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Ningbo has put more than 10 billion
yuan into this effort in a bid to meet the demands of a rapidly
growing local economy.
</P>
<P>
Ningbo now has shpping routes to some 400 ports around the
world. Last year, the port handled some 82 million tons of cargo,
ranking the second in China.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 26 air routes have been opened linking
Ningbo with other cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, an expressway connecting Ningbo with many other
parts of the country is currently under construction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
