<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Upset Over Maids Export Ban by Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti labor offices are
upset over a recent export ban of housemaids by Bangladesh, Nepal,
Indonesia and the Philippines, the Arab Times daily said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The four Asian countries imposed the ban in order to protect
their national image because some of their housemaids, or nurses,
working previously in Kuwait were involved in "immoral"
activities, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the ban was the ill treatment that many
foreign workers received from their Kuwaiti employers.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's labor offices will bear the brunt of the ban because
their profits are to be trimmed due to the cut of supply of cheap
foreign labor, the paper quoted recruitment agents as saying.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Ambassador of Bangladesh to Kuwait Mustafa Rahman was
quoted as saying that his country banned its nationals from
working as housemaids or nurses in Kuwait because many of the
girls previously working in the country had been involved in
immoral activities.
</P>
<P>
Some housemaids got "married" again with Kuwaitis despite
they were already married back home, he said, adding that this
undermined the image of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision was also based on many other factors,
such as the maltreatment of its citizens working as housemaids in
Kuwait and other countries, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign housemaids in Kuwait are often reportedly beaten,
forced to work overtime and even raped by their employers.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they were so underpaid that some of them even can not
make ends meet in the rich Gulf emirate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims Living On Dam Near Dongting Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CHANGSHA, August 3 (Xinhua)--Zhang Xiuying, 68, has been staying
in a make-shift tent on the Hudu River Dam in Anxiang County for
nine days. She doesn't know when, or if, she will be able to move
back to her house.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is one of about 100,000 flood victims in the Dongting Lake
in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
On July 24, the Anzao protective embankment in Anxiang County
was destroyed by floods and 20,000 hectares of fields were
inundated by water.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and her fellow villagers had to abandon their houses and
move to the dam in the rain.
</P>
<P>
Located west of the Dongting Lake, Anxiang County has five
rivers running through and 400-kilometer-long dams and is now one
of the focal points in the flood-control campaign in central and
south China.
</P>
<P>
"I was sleeping at home and ran out without taking clothes when
I heard cries of floods," Zhang said. "It was raining heavily at
that time."
</P>
<P>
Zhang said she could see her house immersed in water from the
dam every day, like a wreck with only its black roof above the
water.
</P>
<P>
Hao Zipeng, Zhang's husband, said the house would probably
collapse even if the flood recedes very soon.
</P>
<P>
The eight-meter-wide dam is crowded with simple camps built for
the victims by the government.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that the camps stretch for 60 kilometers
on the 125-kilometer-dam. Outside the camps are basins, bowls and
pots dredged up from the water.
</P>
<P>
"During the first few days, we lived on the biscuits and
distilled water supplied by the government," Zhang said. "Later,
we got rice, but it is not enough. Now we eat twice every day
without any dishes."
</P>
<P>
But she expressed no worries about the future, saying she heard
that the government had begun to move the victims to dry land.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the weekend 58,000 victims, 56.5 percent of the
villagers on the dam, had been resettled, according to the local
official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
