<HEADLINE> Prince Ranariddh Denies Having Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Prince Norodom Ranariddh, upon
return from Bangkok on Monday, said he had no troops deployed on
the border with Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh went to Bangkok on July 31 after partial results
showed that the ruling Cambodian People's Party would lead
Cambodia's next coalition government following its win in the
July 26 election.
</P>
<P>
When asked about whether he had met his generals commanding his
troops on the Cambodian-Thai border, Ranariddh said he did not
have any troops.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh's troops fought with those of incumbent co-premier
Hun Sen after the prince was ousted as first-premier in July last
year.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh also told reporters that he would not consider
joining a coalition government with his rival Hun Sen, who is set
to become next prime minister, unless his demand for vote
recounting in some areas was met.
</P>
<P>
The prince has claimed fraud in the "unjust" and "unacceptable"
election and called for re-polling in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, the National Election Committee (NEC) said
recounting would soon begin in some communes where
"irregularities" were said to have influenced the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
NEC spokesman Samraing Kamsan told reporters that the NEC would
recount the votes in certain communes after some political parties
complained about election "fraud" there. The commune's names were
not given.
</P>
<P>
But he said the recounting would not cover all "fraud-ridden"
areas as requested by the parties, notably Funcinpec of Prince
Norodom Ranariddh and the opposition Sam Rainsy Party (SRP).
</P>
<P>
According to unverified initial results of the July 26
multi-party election, the ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
won the most votes, to be followed by Funcinpec and the SRP.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec, the SRP and other parties demanded revoting in some
areas, otherwise they would not accept the election results. The
NEC has set up a special panel to investigate alleged
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
In a statement faxed to Xinhua on Monday, the SRP said it has
collected evidence for counting fraud and will present summaries
of the evidence to the press later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The statement invited journalists, election observers and
members of the diplomatic community to "hear the testimony of
Cambodian people who have witnessed serious election fraud and who
have been threatened and attacked before, during and after the
polling and counting of votes."
</P>
<P>
The NEC spokesman said they would handle complaints about
election fraud after the announcement of verified initial results
scheduled for August 4. The final official results will not be
announced until as early as August 19.
</P>
<P>
Votes in 11 provinces out of a total of 23 had been verified by
Monday noon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
