<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Product Quality of Large Enterprises Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- About 95 percent of the products
from large Chinese enterprises meet state standards, according to
a survey which was issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the State Quality and Technology
Supervision Bureau in the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"It indicates a slight improvement in the product quality of
the country's large companies, which has been maintaining a high
level over the past few years," said Zhu Mingxian, deputy-director
of the bureau, at a news conference in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Large enterprises in pillar industries did especially well in
improving product quality, he said, adding that the survey found
all the products from big companies in the chemical industry, the
industries of nonferrous metal, electronics and construction
materials, and 98 percent of those in the metallurgical industry
qualified.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that more than 86 percent of the 700
types of products from medium-sized companies met state standards,
while 70 percent of the 1,500 products from small companies passed
the quality tests.
</P>
<P>
"The product quality of the domestic enterprises has improved a
little in recent years on a general basis," said Zhu, "but there
are still some problems."
</P>
<P>
He said the general proportion of qualified products has been
kept above 75 percent during the past three years, but it never
surpassed the figure of 1990, which was 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The low quality of products of some small collective and
private companies has hindered the overall progress of the
country's product quality," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
About 30-to-50 percent of the products from these companies are
not up to standards, according to the survey. Earlier surveys
found that all milk powder and cooking ranges for home use,
produced by the non-state-owned companies, were not satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said state quality and technology supervision departments
at all levels will still focus on improving the management and
inspection of these enterprises in the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
