<HEADLINE> Drug-related Crimes Rise Rapidly in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Drug-related crimes in Jordan rose
by a record high of 50.9 percent in 1997 compared with 1996, an
official report said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by Jordan's Public Security Department said
that it dealt with 492 cases of the kind in 1997, 166 cases more
than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 803 people were involved in the drug-related cases last
year, up 22 percent from 1996, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed the rise in drug-related crimes to
more people moving from rural to urban areas and the increase of
foreign workers in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not elaborate on the figures.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Jordanian police seized 82 kilograms of heroin, a 22
percent rise from 1996, and 3 million pills, 10 times of that in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is used as a transit route by drug traffickers from
Lebanon and Turkey, which has also contributed to the increase of
drug crimes in the kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
