<HEADLINE> Uganda to Set up More Radio, TV Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 13 private FM radio
stations and three television companies have applied for
broadcasting licenses in Uganda, making the competition for the
airwaves tougher than ever.
</P>
<P>
If all the applicants are registered, Uganda will have
altogether 26 radio sations and eight TV stations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will build another 20 FM radio and
television stations at selected locations within the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
The 4.5-million-U.S. Dollar project is expected to increase
the revenue for the state-owned Radio Uganda and Uganda
Television, which has been plummeting since the liberalization of
the airwaves in Uganda in 1993, the East African weekly reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The radio and television stations are now moving toward
specification as they struggle for a niche in the market.
</P>
<P>
With the newcomers into the advertizing market, the old ones
say they'd like to face the challenge.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Quarcoo, the managing director of Capital Radio, said
"The new companies are welcome. We are not worried as we believe
in competition." 
</P>
