<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Giant Coal Producer Hopes to Become Clean-Energy Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanxi Province, China's leading
coal producer, is hoping to turn itself into China's largest
clean-energy base in years.
</P>
<P>
Known as "a sea of coal," the province has verified coal
reserves of 287.3 billion tons, one-third of the country's total.
It now produces 300 million tons of coal annually.
</P>
<P>
Intensified coal exploration and extensive processing in the
province have caused worsening environmental problems such as
serious air pollution, leaving a 200-kilometer-long smoke
pollution belt from the provincial capital of Taiyuan to Linfen
city and the waste from a huge amount of chemical raw materials.
</P>
<P>
To change this situation, the province plans to upgrade coke
furnaces which lack recovery facilities in the Fenhe River
Valleys, and concentrate hundreds of smaller ovens in the same
valley into several groups where large modern coke ovens will be
installed during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Urban residents in the region will be encouraged to use coal
gas to reduce the discharge of pollutants, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
Several large tar-processing centers and coal-gasification
enterprises will be built. Discarded materials from coal
exploration and in-depth processing will be treated to reduce
pollutant discharge to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
While improving the utilization rate of coal resources, the
province will increase efforts to develop and spread clean-energy
technology and energy-efficient equipment to turn Shanxi into a
region with both a healthy environment and a highly developed
economy.
</P>
<P>
The province will also introduce advanced foreign technologies
in its drive to make Shanxi a clean-energy base, which may cost an
estimated 10 billion yuan, according to local sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
