<HEADLINE> Unemployed Kenyans Top Three Million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- More than three million people
in Kenya are unemployed, according to Gerald Gicheru, the
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another 500,000 people entered the job market every
year but only 150,000 of them managed to get jobs, he was quoted
by Monday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Decrying the high unemployment rate, he noted that more
emphasis must be put on the informal sector which had emerged as
the biggest employer today.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan population had risen from eight million at
independence in 1963 to about 30 million today, a figure, which
Gicheru said must be controlled.
</P>
<P>
"The high population growth has greatly strained the economy
and the country's resources, thus affecting the provision of
government services to the public," he said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The official also urged Kenyans to acquire technical skills in
order to be assured of employment in the job market.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt today that graduates from technical
institutions are in high demand in the job market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government, he added, will retrench 169,000 employees in
the next few years in order to cope with the difficult economic
times. 
</P>
