<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summer Camp for Obese Kids in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- No fried chicken, no braised
pork, no buttered bread. Life was really hard for 13-year-old Yu
Chi last week.
</P>
<P>
Yu weighs over 100 kilograms and, along with 52 other obese
children between 10 and 14 years old, was participating in a
week-long summer camp program for overweight kids in Shanghai,
China's largest commercial city.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of camp, two beds were broken when two of the
kids sat on them, said one camp counselor.
</P>
<P>
Children must get up at six o'clock every morning and then do
exercises such as running and swimming in the sweltering summer
heat.
</P>
<P>
In addition to physical exercises, the camp highlights
cultivating good daily habits in the children, said the teacher,
adding that they must make their beds and wash their own clothes.
</P>
<P>
Doctors from local hospitals have been invited to present
classes teaching the children about the harm of obesity and how to
scientifically reduce their weight. The children's diet while at
the camp is planned by professional nutritionists.
</P>
<P>
China adopted the one-child policy some two decades ago. Since
then, Chinese parents have pampered their children with affection
and allowed them to over-indulgence in junk food.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that Chinese children now consume too much fat and
sugar while sitting in front of the TV all day long and almost
never exercising.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that three out of every 100 Shanghai
children under the age of six suffer from obesity, 6.24 times the
rate of a decade ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM, Iraq Start Talks on Weapons Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 3 (Xinhua)-- The U.N. Special Commission for
disarmament in Iraq, known as UNSCOM, opened talks with Iraqi
officials here Monday amid Iraq's call for end to its prolonged
inspection mission.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler did not speak to reporters
before his meeting with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz at
the Iraqi Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his current visit here, Butler told reporters
Sunday evening that the UNSCOM wants to wrap up its work
quickly. He said during the talks, the two sides would review the
working program reached between the two sides weeks ago during
Butler's last visit to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"We will check together what the progress has been, what
has been achieved, what may still need to be done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Butler termed as "very important" his talks with Aziz, saying
he hoped they could get to the end of the disarmament phase as
soon as possible so the United Nations Security Council could
consider whether to lift the eight year long sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Iraq has been accusing the UNSCOM and the U.N.
Security Council of not awarding its cooperation with the UNSCOM
and the International Atomic Energy Agency on their weapons
inspection mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Due to the strong opposition by the United States and Britain,
the Security Council failed last Wednesday to accept a Russian
proposal for scaling back the U.N. inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein made it clear in a nationally
televised address last month that Iraq would adopt "alternative
strategy" should its cooperation with the UNSCOM did not lead to
the lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has imposed comprehensive economic sanctions
on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, and the sanctions
cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM verifies that it is free of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM is to present its next report on the Iraqi weapons
inspection to the U.N. Security Council in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
