<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Tigers Born in Changchun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Siberian tiger has recently
given birth to three cubs in Changchun, capital of northeast
China's Jilin Province, bringing to nine the number of newly-born
tigers at the Changchun Zoo.
</P>
<P>
The three cubs, born on July 3, now weighs more than one
kilogram each.
</P>
<P>
This was the ninth birth of the 13-year-old mother tiger, Yan
Chun. In June, it had a miscarriage and gave
birth to a dead cub. "Usually, a miscarriage may lead to the
premature delivery of the other cubs, which would probably not
survive," said a zookeeper.
</P>
<P>
The zookeepers at once adopted measures to prevent the
premature delivery of the other cubs. The three cubs are now in
good condition, often crouching around Yan Chun and jostling with
each other to nurse at their mother's breast.
</P>
<P>
The zookeepers said that at present they could not determine
the sex of the cubs.
</P>
<P>
The other six month-old cubs at the zoo, one male and five
females, were born to two other tigers. The six now weigh about
seven kilograms each.
</P>
<P>
The Siberian tiger is a species on the world's top protection
list.  
</P>
</TEXT>
