<HEADLINE> Uganda's Imported Copters Not Airworthy: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The four second-hand helicopters
imported by the Ugandan military have proved not airworthy and
the sale agreement has been seriously breached, an investigation
report said.
</P>
<P>
The report has been made by a Uganda-invited South African
firm in response to allegations that the planes have not met the
standards required, the Nairobi-based East African weekly
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Based on the findings of the report, Uganda's Ministry of
Justice is planning to take legal action against the supplier,
Consolidated Sales Corporation (CSC) reportedly owned by Uganda's
rally ace Emmanuel Katto.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government is reported to have made the purchase
of the four MI 24 helicopters from the Republic of Belarus in
April 1997 for more than 12 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Up to now only two of the combat aircraft have been delivered
to Uganda. They are supposed to be overhauled before shipment
and to be in good mechanical conditions as stipulated in the
sales contract.
</P>
<P>
Bart Katureebe, the attorney-general, was quoted as saying
last week: "I have raised the matter with the suppliers. We shall
take actions on their reply."
</P>
<P>
On July 13, President Yoweri Museveni's Senior Presidential
Adviser John Nagenda issued a statement saying the CSC was
introduced to the military by an impeccable contact he did not
name.
</P>
<P>
Uganda opted for the second hand aircraft because the
government could not afford the new ones which will cost eight
million U.S. Dollars each and the military need them badly to
boost its air strike capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
