<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM to Visit Iran to Amend Strained Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad
Anani will pay an official visit to Tehran on Saturday in a bid to
amend bilateral ties that have been strained in the past years.
</P>
<P>
"After a break of several years, we believe that with the new
political leadership in Iran, the time is ripe to develop and
enhance bilateral ties on all levels," the semi-official Jordan
Times Monday quoted Anani as saying.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Tehran, Anani is expected to deliver a
good-will message from King Hussein of Jordan to Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami and invite him to pay an official visit to the
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Anani will also meet his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi
and other officials to discuss means of political and economic
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues to be raised with Iranian officials are
Iranian-Arab relations, elimination of mass destruction weapons in
the Middle East, as well as the Arab-Israeli peace process, Anani
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anani will also discuss with Iranian officials ways
of increasing bilateral trade and industrial cooperation. The
establishment of a joint venture in Jordan to produce phosphate
fertilizer that will be mostly exported to Iran is on the agenda
of the upcoming talks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Tehran severed its diplomatic ties with Amman to protest the
kingdom's one-sided support to Iraqi during the 1980-1988
Iraqi-Iranian war.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic ties between Jordan and Iran were restored in
1990.
</P>
<P>
However, the bilateral ties have been strained since 1995 when
Jordan expelled First Secretary at the Iranian Embassy Saeed
Batini, accusing him of "performing acts that contradicted with
his diplomatic status."
</P>
<P>
After the moderate Khatami was elected Iranian President last
year, the ice in the bilateral ties began to thaw amid Tehran's
efforts to improve relations with all countries, especially with
most of the Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan visited Iran to
attend the a meeting of the Organization of Islamic Conference,
during which he met Khatami and other senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
