<HEADLINE> Study Detects Widespread Smoking Among Kuwaiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Up to 64 percent of the male
secondary students in Kuwait are smokers, the Arab Times newspaper
quoted a report as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted recently by the Kuwaiti Health Ministry said
that this was a 18 percent rise from 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the study found that male adult smokers in Kuwait have
declined. More than 42 percent of the men over the age of 20 were
smoking last year, 10 percentage points lower than in 1992.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that 14 percent of the adult women are smokers,
adding that more and more female university students have turned
to smoking.
</P>
<P>
Smoking has resulted in many diseases. The cases of lung cancer
increased by 412 percent among females and 118 percent among males
between 1992 and 1997, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The rate of heart attacks and strokes at an early age (around
40) also keeps rising, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
