<HEADLINE> Eight-Year-Old Giant Panda Deliver Her Second Cub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- An eight-year-old giant panda
gave birth to her second cub recently after a four-month pregnancy
in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The mother panda, named "No.28," was artificially inseminated
this past March.
</P>
<P>
The mother and her baby are in good conditions now at the China
Research Center of Giant Panda Protection in the Wolong Nature
Preserve, habitat of the giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is a rare wild animal species on verge of
extinction. It is believed there are only around 1,000 giant
pandas in the world, most of them living in the mountains around
the Sichuan Basin.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda has a low reproductivity rate, and it is
believed that only about 24 percent of the female giant pandas are
able to conceive.
</P>
<P>
Since the research center was established in 1991, it has help
breed 21 baby pandas, and 15 of them have survived.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
