<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLA Insurance Regulations Go Into Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A set of regulations became
effective on August 1, the Army Day, insuring all members of the
People's Liberation Army (PLA) against losses of life and injuries.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate that if a Chinese service man
is killed in action, his beneficiary can expect to receive, in
addition to his pension, a guaranteed sum that is 10 times higher
than the pension.
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhiqiang, head of the PLA Army Men Insurance Office, said
the establishment of the insurance fund is aimed at offering
compensation to the families of soldiers who are killed or
handicapped in action, or who become handicapped because of illness.
</P>
<P>
He said that this is the first time an insurance system has
been introduced into the PLA, and that it is aimed at maintaining
the rights and interests of the PLA personnel.
</P>
<P>
The official said that past regulations focused on the
pension. However, the pension is quite low and the rights and
interests of soldiers could not be guaranteed in that way.
</P>
<P>
He said that endowment and medical insurance for those retired
from the army will also be introduced when conditions are mature.
</P>
<P>
These new regulations were joinly issued by the PLA's
Headquarters of the General Staff, the General Political
Department, the General Logistics Department and the General
Armament Department.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory servicemen, civil servicemen and volunteer
soldiers are required to pay a certain amount as an insurance
premium, which is no more than one percent of their monthly salaries.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred thousand officers and soldiers retire from the
military every year, and thousands of them are handicapped or ill,
and many are met with the problems of low pensions and future
employment.
</P>
<P>
This insurance plan for servicemen was granted by the State
Council and the Central Military Commission in July this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Adapt Better to High Altitudes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Women's adaptability to the
low-oxygen of high altitudes is much better than men, according to
a recent physiological study of both men and women who have moved
to the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Wu Tianyi, a Chinese altitude-medicine specialist, said that
women are born with better adaptability because men and women
secrete different hormones.
</P>
<P>
People who first move from the plains to the plateau are apt to
suffer altitude disease as their red blood cells increase due to
oxygen deficit.
</P>
<P>
The medical study found that female sex hormones, called
estrogen, can check the hyperplasia of red blood cells, while the
male sex hormones increase the number of these cells. In addition,
menstruation also lowers red blood cells in women.
</P>
<P>
Also, thoracic breathing is found to be quite common among
women while abdominal breathing is more frequently found among
men. Chinese experts noted that under the same conditions,
thoracic breathing can supply more oxygen.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, progeterone in women stimulates the human
respiration center to inhale more oxygen under low-oxygen
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The study of female adaptability to high-altitude environments
has just begun, but this new knowledge is expected to have a great
impact on health protection for people living on the plateau,
according to scientists.
</P>
<P>
In China, estrogen is already being used to treat chronic
altitude sickness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai Increases Fixed Assets Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai Province
pumped 2.85 billion yuan into fixed assets from January to June,
a rise of 36.7 percent over the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
This investment was 22.9 percent more than the national average
for the first half, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The province generated 7.64 billion yuan of gross domestic
product (GDP) in the first six months of this year, up 7.8 percent
from the comparable figure last year. This rate of increase is
the highest among all provinces and autonomous regions in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute the province's sound economic
development to the fast growth of fixed assets investment which is
estimated to have contributed 70 percent to the province's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Heavy industry makes up over 80 percent of the province's
industrial economy as Qinghai abounds in natural resources. Since
the beginning of this year, the province has hastened the
production of electrolytic aluminum, steel products, cement, and
chemical fertilizers, and the construction of infrastructure and
service industries. Marked increases of investment in power,
transportation, oil and gas, agriculture, services, real estate,
and infrastructure also were reported in the first six months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The province also introduced 15.08 million U.S. dollars of
overseas funds for investing into its fixed assets in the first
half, a rise of 31 percent over last year's comparable figure.
</P>
