<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diarrhea, Dysentery Break out in Bangladesh's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Diarrhea, dysentery and fever have
already affected over 40,000 people in Bangladesh's flood-hit
areas with 30 lives claimed so far, a media report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Leader of various section of people in the flood-affected areas
have called for effective measures to check the outbreak of
diarrhea and other water-borne diseases with receding of flood
water.
</P>
<P>
"It's time to take necessary steps to prevent the epidemic of
diarrhea and other diseases in the country's flood-affected areas
to check further deaths," they said.
</P>
<P>
Health officials at the flood-hit areas were unable to face the
threat of such diseases caused by people drinking polluted water
and eating rotten food, they added.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh red Crescent Society has issued a global appeal
of 1.7 million U.S. dollars' aid for the flood victims, and
requested the World Health Organization to send about five million
water-purifying tablets to ensure pure drinking water for the
marooned people and keep safe from the diseases in the aftermath
of flood.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been hit by flood due to constant heavy rainfall
since early last month.
</P>
<P>
Up to Sunday, 37 districts out of the total of 64 have been
seriously flooded, with over 17.5 million people being hit and
flood-related death toll rising to 256.
</P>
<P>
The flood has also damaged and washed away over 5,000
kilometers of roads, 1,722 kilometers of embankment and 2,215
bridges and nearly 200,000 hectares of standing crops, causing
heavy losses for the country.
</P>
<P>
The government departments concerned have already distributed
more than 11 million taka (234,000 dollars), over 3,000 tons of
grain and other relief materials among the flood victims. The have
also sent several thousand medical teams to the flood-hit
districts to treat patients with water-borne diseases and control
of their spread.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided not to seek outside financial aid
and succor to the victims of the flood.
</P>
<P>
However, the overall flood situation across the country marked
slight improvement on Sunday with receding of water in all major
rivers, according to the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
