<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Visits Grenada 15 Years After U.S. Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro
arrived Sunday on the Caribbean island of Grenada, where U.S. and
Cuban forces fought face-to-face 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Grenadian Prime Minister Keith Mitchell greeted the 71-year-old
Cuban leader at the Point Salines airport.
</P>
<P>
Castro said after a welcoming ceremony that he was pleased to
see a rebirth of cooperation and friendship between the two
peoples.
</P>
<P>
"We can assure you that Cuba will continue its modest
cooperation in solidarity with Grenada's developments," he added.
</P>
<P>
A state dinner hosted by Governor General Daniel Williams was
scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday Castro will meet with Prime Minister Mitchell and
slain Prime Minister Maurice Bishop's widow at her home.
</P>
<P>
On Monday afternoon, there will be a rally followed by a
reception. The Cuban leader is slated to leave late Monday.
</P>
<P>
Just 34 kilometers long and 20 kilometers wide, Grenada has a
population of 97,000.
</P>
<P>
On October 25, 1983, U.S. troops invaded the island after
Grenadian Prime Minister Maurice Bishop was murdered along with
most of his cabinet by dissidents in his New Jewel political
movement.
</P>
<P>
The invasion resulted in the deaths of 18 U.S. soldiers and 34
Cuban construction workers.
</P>
<P>
Grenada and Cuba broke off relations during the 18-month U.S.
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Grenada is the last stop of Castro's three-nation Caribbean
tour which has taken him to Jamaica and Barbados. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
