<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Bank Governor Urges Unemployment Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The governor of Italy's central bank
has urged current expenditure reductions, tax cuts and public
investment for increasing infrastructures, especially in poor
areas.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Fazio, governor of the Bank of Italy, held these as the
key measures for reducing unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Another measure should be a new income policy linking wages
more closely with productivity, the governor said Sunday in a rare
 interview with the Italian daily, La Repubblica.
</P>
<P>
Governors of the Italian central bank usually make their views
known in official speeches and reports.
</P>
<P>
The interview gave no hint about one thing that all businessmen
and financial operators are keen to know: the bank's next
reduction in its discount rate.
</P>
<P>
But amid general expectations that there must be a cut sometime
now, he explained that decisions of this kind are strictly
technical and are not "regulated to assign rewards or punishments
to the government or society's components."
</P>
<P>
Monetary policy decisions of the bank are taken in terms of
"objective parameters" such as prices, liquidity, the state of the
public accounts and the general economic conditions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fazio hinted that any other way of envisaging the bank's tasks
would represent a relinquishment of its independence from
political pressure.
</P>
<P>
Fazio added that the welfare reform is needed, but should be
achieved with "wide-spread consent" so as to preserve its basic
aims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
