<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing New Way To Treat Mental Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese psychiatrists have
developed a new way of treating mental illnesses by using
traditional Taoist philosophy.
</P>
<P>
This "Chinese Taoist Cognative Treatment" has been claimed to
be especially suited to the psychology of the Chinese people. Its
effectiveness has been confirmed by clinical experience in 16
provinces and cities over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Zhang Yalin, one of the people who developed it, says that
the reason they chose Taoism as the theoretical base was that
Taoist thought has a special effect on the mentality of the
Chinese, who often resort to it for consolation in times of
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Taoist philosophy emphasizes benefitting
without hurting and acting without striving, restricting
selfishness and individual desire, being in harmony with others,
and obeying the law of nature.
</P>
<P>
The five-step treatment begins with identifying the causes of
the patient's mental distress and the subjective reasons for his
or her stressful reaction. Then the patient is helped to adjust by
learning from Taoist philosophy to resolve the conflict until a
new way of thinking is firmly established in his mind.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Zhang said the results are more encouraging when combined
with the use of medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
