<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Expanding to Suburbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Two suburban counties becoming
districts of Beijing are a significant sign that the capital city
is expanding its urban territory by leaps and bounds.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, Tongxian County in East
Beijing was converted into Tongzhou District of Beijing last year
and Shunyi County in the northeastern suburb will become another
"District" this December.
</P>
<P>
"After the change, the two newly added districts will be
considered part of Beijing's urban area," said Li Shaochun with
the basic-level government under the Beijing Bureau of Civil
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has a total of 12 districts and six counties at present.
</P>
<P>
In the future, Beijing will form a three-ring pattern with 10
districts in the urban area, two districts, Daxing and Changping
counties in the suburbs and the remaining four counties in the
outer suburbs, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's county-to-district conversion is just part of the
national urbanization process, the China Daily said. Statistics
show that the number of Chinese cities has tripled since 1980 to
stand at 666.
</P>
<P>
The change of the two counties into districts is expected to
lessen pressure on the capital's urban traffic and other
infrastructure capabilities.
</P>
<P>
"The conversion of counties into districts will attract more
commuters to settle down in the suburbs," Li said, explaining that
in China, being a city person still spells higher social status.
</P>
<P>
For Zhang Deqin, office chief of the Tongzhou District, the
change is even more realistically significant.
</P>
<P>
"More investment has been offered to our district and local
estate is booming," he said. "I was told that during the first
half the year, the district sold all the houses we originally
planned to sell in the whole year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
