<HEADLINE> Denmark Provides Grants for Thai Rural Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Denmark has agreed to provide 133
million baht (3.33 million U.S. dollars) in grants to assist
community-based environment projects in Thailand over the next
four years, the Bangkok Post said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Mogens Dyhr-Nielson, program director of
Danish Cooperation for Environment and Development (Danced), as
saying that the success of the projects to mobilize rural
inhabitants to support environmental projects promoted his agency
to continue the funding of the projects.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Danced allocated 62 million baht (1.55 million
dollars) for three community-based natural resource management
projects for northern and northeastern farmer networks and the
federation of fishermen in the South.
</P>
<P>
Anek Nakhabutr, coordinator of Thai NGO Coordinating Committee
and Danced Partnership Program, said the assistance helped
facilitate the formation of farmer and fishermen networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
