<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Building Its First Wind-Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a 100,000-kw
wind-power station is now underway in Tongyu Prefecture in
northeast China's Jilin Province, the first power plant of its
kind in the province.
</P>
<P>
The project will be built in five phases. The first phase will
cost more than 87 million yuan, including 5.34 million
U.S. dollars of investment from Spain.
</P>
<P>
The second phase is due to commerce in March 1999 and will use
loans from the Danish Government.
</P>
<P>
Located at the juncture of the Changbai Mountains and the Great
Hinggan Mountains, Tongyu Prefecture is the passage for the
Siberian airflow heading southwards.
</P>
<P>
Wind-power stations can be built within a circumference of more
than 500 square kilometers in the prefecture, where wind normally
blows at an average speed of 6.95 meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to its rich wind resources, an installed capacity
totalling 300,000 kw can be achieved in Tongyu, making
it one of the largest wind-power producer in the country.
</P>
<P>
The province expects to get into the sustained development of
local energy by increasing its use of this clean energy source.
</P>
<P>
China has several wind-power stations in its northwest and
coastal areas and intends to install one million kw
of wind-driven generators in the next three to five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
