<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Keeps Unbeaten at Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia proved its dominance at
the Men's World Basketball Championship by trouncing Canada 95-55
in Sunday's second round game.
</P>
<P>
The European champion decided the victory only 10 minutes into
the first half.
</P>
<P>
Even without its two best players _ Vlade Divac of the
Charlotte Hornets and former NBAer Predrag Danilovic _ and
playmaker Aleksandar Djordjevic battling injury, Yugoslavia has
looked like it could add this title to its 1990 world gold.
</P>
<P>
"They got on a roll and we couldn't stop their roll," said
Canada's coach, Steve Konchalski. "When we got the ball inside in
the first half, they seemed to block every shot."
</P>
<P>
Spain beat Brazil 73-63 while Greece edged Puerto Rico 71-64,
both improved to 4-0.
</P>
<P>
The Americans (3-1) didn't pull away from Argentina until late
but put together their best overall game of the tournament to win
87-74. Wendell Alexis scored 20 points and Jimmy Oliver had 18.
</P>
<P>
It was a two-point game with 4:00 minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
U.S. coach Rudy Tomjanovich said that his team was never fully
in control, allowing Argentina (2-2) to get within shouting
distance repeatedly. Marcelo Nicola led the South Americans with
26 points, and Fabricio Oberto added 18.
</P>
<P>
Alexis had 15, including three 3-pointers from the corners, in
a 5-minute stretch of the first half when the United States built
the first of its short-lived leads.
</P>
<P>
The victory moved the Americans into second place in their
group, tied with Lithuania at 3-1. The United States will meet
Spain next game.
</P>
<P>
Spain was led by guards Alberto Angulo and Ignacio Rodriguez,
both scored 17 points apiece when Spain trailed by as many as
seven points in the early stages.
</P>
<P>
Joao Jose Vianna had 15 points for Brazil (1-3).
</P>
<P>
Forward Nicos Economou's 19 points helped Greece keep pace
with Yugoslavia atop the other six-team group by defeating Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
The hosts led by 13 at halftime, but Puerto Rico (1-3), led by
Eddie Casiano's 19 points, closed the gap down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere Sunday, Russia (3-1) secured a 71-55 win over Italy
(2-2) on the strength of Sergei Babkov's 26 points and Mikhail
Mikhailov's 15 rebounds, and Australia (2-2) handed Lithuania its
first loss, 71-61, as Seton Hall product Andrew Gaze scored 24,
including 10 straight down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
The top four teams in each group reach the quarterfinals, and
Sunday's losses mean Canada, Brazil and Puerto Rico have virtually
no chance of advancing.
</P>
<P>
In consolation games, Nigeria defeated South Korea 89-65 and
Japan topped Senegal 66-55.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
