<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Urged to Punish Rioters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A known political commentator
Monday urged the Indonesian government to bring to justice the
real culprits in a series of riots on May 13 to 15 in Jakarta,
capital of Indonesia, and other cities.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary published by the Jakarta Post, chairman of the
supervisory board of the Center for Strategic and International
Studies Jusuf Wanandi called the May riots similar to "ethnic
cleansing" campaigns in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia saw the worst looting and rioting in decades in
Jakarta and other cities. About 1,200 lives were claimed, and
thousands of buildings and vehicles were damaged and burnt.
</P>
<P>
According to a non-governmental organization, the total number
of victims of rape and sexual harassment from the rioting has now
reached 168.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said the riots, looting, burning and rapes in
May have left Chinese Indonesian "bewildered, rudderless and
desperate".
</P>
<P>
"If the planners of the riots wanted to scare the Chinese
Indonesians, they have succeeded. But they have also succeeded in
hurting Indonesia itself," the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
Describing as a watershed period for Chinese Indonesians, the
commentary called on the government to win back this community.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese Indonesians will only plow money into the economy
after they have regained trust in Indonesia's future," it said.
</P>
<P>
For this, the commentary said, most vital is a full accounting
of the May riots.
</P>
<P>
"President B.J. Habibie's effort to recognize the traumatic May
events and apologize on behalf of the government is a good start.
And the creation of an independent national committee to
investigate the rapes is welcomed. The investigation must go to
the root of the problem, even if its trail leads to powerful
people," the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
In the medium term, there must be an open dialog on the future
status, rights and obligations of Chinese Indonesians in the
country's national development. This should produce acceptable
policies for both the minority Chinese Indonesians and the
majority native Indonesians, the commentary added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
