<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Reports Drop in Pharmaceutical Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has witnessed a sharp
drop in imports of foreign pharmaceutical products due to
implementation of a new medical reform program which requires
local residents to pay for certain types of imported products.
</P>
<P>
Beijing import 137 tons of foreign medical products during the
first half of the year, down 50 percent on the same period last
year, according statistics released by the Beijing Customs Office.
</P>
<P>
The overall decline in imports was the direct result of the
fall in imports of pharmaceuticals excluded from the list of
reimbursable medical products.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the overall trade volume of imported medical
products hit 14.45 million US dollars, up 3.6 percent on the 1997
period.
</P>
<P>
Experts explained that the total import value continued to rise
in spite of the falling volume due to price hikes for various
foreign medicines.
</P>
<P>
Joint ventures and foreign-funded companies account for the
bulk of enterprises engaged in the pharmaceutical import sector,
with related ventures accounting for more than 85 percent of the
total import volume.
</P>
<P>
China witnessed further optimization of the structure for
imported medicines during the first half of the year, with a rise
in imports of related raw materials and drop in imports
preparations. The change clearly indicates the growing production
capacity of China's pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of pharmaceutical joint ventures and
foreign-funded companies in Beijing were founded by companies from
Switzerland, Germany and France, as well as various other European
nations. Said countries also supply the bulk of raw materials for
medical products, with a lesser volume coming from the United
States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
