<HEADLINE>   Italy, Libya Reopen Marine Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Libya on Sunday reopened
their marine transportation of cargoes and passengers in a move
towards a more dynamic course in bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday morning, a Libyan ship, Toletela, arrived in Catania
on the island of Sicily from the Libyan port city of Tripoli, and
would start its return voyage in evening.
</P>
<P>
Two ships of General National Maritime Transport Co. of Libya
will serve the line between Tripoli, capital of the
Arabian-majority African nation, and Catania.
</P>
<P>
Each ship has a cargo capacity of 6,000 tons with a maximum of
768 passengers.
</P>
<P>
Sea traffic between the two countries had been cut off in the
wake of sanctions imposed on Libya by the United Nations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The embargo came after Libya's refusal to extradite to London
or Washington two Libyans suspected of involvement in the December
1988 bombing of a U.S. passenger plane over Lockerbie, Scotland
that killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
But bilateral links have eased based on an accord signed on
July 9 aimed at normalizing relations and bringing an end to the
negative impact of the past.
</P>
<P>
One of their odds between Italy and Libya, which was colonized
by Rome from 1911 to 1943, had been the question of financial
compensation for the colonial period.
</P>
<P>
Regardless of their odds, the two nations have built up strong
economic links, with Italian imports, mostly oil, totaling 3.78
billion U.S. dollars from Libya last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
