<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai GM to Roll Out First Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai GM, China's largest car
joint venture, is set to roll out its first mid-sized car model,
the Buick, in December, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Hu Maoyuan, president of Shanghai GM, as saying
that the goal is to enable "made-in-China Buicks" to compete
favorably with imported luxury saloon cars.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai GM is a 1.52 billion US dollar joint venture between
China's largest passenger car manufacturer, Shanghai Automotive
Industry Corp (SAIC), and the world famous manufacturer of
automobiles, General Motors (GM).
</P>
<P>
Five work shops, involving pressing, body welding, painting,
general assembly and power chain production, have been
completed. Equipment installation is expected to be concluded by
the end of August.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles will feature 2.98-liter 6-valve engines and
automatic transmissions, automobile components to be manufactured
in China for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai GM will manufacture 100,000 vehicles, 180,000 engines
and 100,000 transmissions when it goes into full production.
</P>
<P>
The cars will be sold in China and other Asian countries. In
addition, some parts that have been localized for Shanghai GM
vehicles will be exported throughout the region and to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Employees of Shanghai GM will grow to 3,000 at peak
capacity. An average of 375 hours of training will be provided to
each employee before production begins, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
