<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slater Elected New President of NZ Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Auckland businessman John
Slater was elected President of the National Party, a major ruling
party in New Zealand, at its 62nd annual conference in Auckland at
the weekend, a Wellington-based newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
That means the National Party put Slater into the vital job of
managing next year's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Slater has been a party member for 37 years and is the chairman
of National's powerful northern division, which includes all the
Auckland electorates.
</P>
<P>
"It's a huge responsibility but I've served a long
apprenticeship and I believe I've got the skills and the ability
to do it," The Dominion quoted Slater as saying after the
election.
</P>
<P>
Key issues affecting National's chances at the next election,
which is due in November next year unless the Government calls it
earlier, would be improvement in the economy and a public
perception of confidence in the future, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Slater runs his own textile importing business, which he
started from scratch. He took over the presidency from Geoff
Thompson, who had held the position for four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
