<DOCNO> XIE19980803.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Calls for Smaller Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Jenny Shipley, New Zealand
Prime Minister and the leader of the National Party, a major
ruling party in New Zealand, has called for fewer government
departments and reduced size of the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The call was raised when she was addressing the 62nd annual
conference of the National Party, which was held in Auckland at
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In her keynote address, which was released here Monday by the
Office of the Prime Minister, Mrs. Shipley stressed that small
government "is one of the principles" in the National Party.
</P>
<P>
"The size of Parliament, the size of the Cabinet, the size of
the bureaucracy are all things that you and I need to have a clear
view on. I believe that we do have a historical view of being
wedded to smaller government and larger private sector
participation," she told the 600 delegates to the conference.
</P>
<P>
Dealing with the electoral reform, the Prime Minister called on
New Zealanders to debate the issue with respect to the size of the
Parliament. She indicated that she favors for reducing the number
of MPs from the current 120 to 100 and supports change in the
current "Mixed Member Proportional" (MMP) electoral voting system.
</P>
<P>
Under this electoral voting system, each voter has two votes,
one for an electorate MP and the other for a political party. Each
party's share of the total number of MPs is decided by its share
of the nationwide party vote. This total is made up of electorate
MPs and MPs elected from the party lists published before the
General Election.
</P>
<P>
"I believe some change will be required in the future ...... I
personally support change," Mrs. Shipley said at the conference.
</P>
<P>
In her address, Mrs. Shipley also reiterated that her
government would continue to allow greater private sector
involvement in the areas of business now controlled by Government.
</P>
<P>
She said she was not advocating a "wild-eyed privatization bid"
but recognizing that "where the private sector can do it better,
we will allow them to do that."
</P>
<P>
A Wellington-based newspaper said in a today's report that the
National Party's moves to dump MMP "have opened a fresh rift" in
the present coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Winston Peter, deputy prime minister and the leader of New
Zealand First, the partner of the National Party in forming the
coalition government, was quoted by The Dominion as saying that
opponents of MMP "simply do not want to share the political
power".
</P>
<P>
Although Peter did not name the National Party as one of those
opponents, his comments were clearly directed at Mrs. Shipley's
remarks at the National Party conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
