<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Benefiting from Mainland's Scientific Findings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A recent exposition showed that
Taiwan's scientific community is benefiting from the Chinese
mainland's technological findings, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
About 200 mainland scientists were sent to Taiwan from July 11
to 22 on academic exchanges, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two seminars were held in the International Convention
Center of Taibei, where 246 technological findings were exhibited.
</P>
<P>
"The findings -- involving telecommunications, electronics,
machinery, materials, chemical industry, petroleum and space and
aviation -- received acclaim from Taiwan scientific and industrial
circles," the paper quoted an official from the Ministry of
Science and Technology as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official is from the ministry's Center of Science and
Technology Exchange Across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The exposition, designed to enhance cross-straits relations,
was sponsored jointly by the center and the Taiwan General
Industrial Federation. The theme was "building links through
science and technology."
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, the largest of its kind, indicated that the
mainland's theoretical research level is higher than Taiwan's. But
the production and commercialization of research findings in
Taiwan are more efficient than on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan scientists are particularly interested in the mainland's
technology of environmental protection, oil exploitation, shipping
and superconduction, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The scientists also discussed scientific policies and
intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Bright prospects exist for scientific co-operation across the
straits because the technological development of both sides is
complementary, said one of the researchers, who has attended the
exposition.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 mainland scientists have visited their Taiwan
counterparts, and thousands of Taiwan scientists have traveled to
the mainland over the years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
