<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Grape King" Able to Defend Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Rozi Niyaz of Turpan, China's
leading grape growing area, will be able to win the title the
"king of grape" for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the then 44-year-old grape grower reaped a record
91.5 tons of grapes per hectare, as against an average of 34.5
tons per hectare, thus becoming Turpan's champion.
</P>
<P>
With dry weather and abundant sunshine, Turpan, located in
Xinjiang Uygur Automonous Region, is a world-renowned grape
producer, especially famous for a seedless white grape variety.
</P>
<P>
Because of favorable climate conditions and improved
agro-technology, experts expect the gross and single output of
grapes and raisin of Turpan will be still higher this year than
last year.
</P>
<P>
Rozi Niyaz is from Lianmuqing Township, a leader of grape
growing in Turpan, with all 5,000 local households engaged in the
business. Last year, the township reaped an average per-ha yield
of 34.5 tons from its 1,300 hectares of vineyards, with, well
above an average yield of 25.5 tons per hectare in Turpan area.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Rozi earned 60,000 yuan (7,228 US dollars) alone
from his 0.4 hectares of vineyards.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the grape, Rozi, the champion defender, is
especially upbeat: "I'm fully confident I'll keep my title this
year."
</P>
<P>
The farmer-turned horticulturist attributes his success to
spreading fertilizers in a scientific way and superb pruning
methods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
