<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- The opposition leader Kim Beazley is poised to take the
Australian Labor Party into a new era of immigration policy
Monday, declaring immigration is good for Australia, and he is
also expected to take head-on the immigration policies of One
Nation Party.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- More than 400,000 Sydney residents received the all-clear
Sunday to drink tap water but the state government has admitted
that it may never know what caused the contamination crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Corporations would face fines of up to 10 million Australian
dollars (6.2 million U.S. dollars) if they failed to pass on to
consumers the widespread tax cuts to be delivered by the
government's tax package, Treasurer Peter Costello said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- Rio Tinto Ltd. is running the ruler over BHP's minerals
division in a move that could trigger one of the biggest mergers
and corporate shake-outs in Australia's history, according to
analysts in London's City financial district. 
</P>
</TEXT>
