<HEADLINE> Torian Steals Limelight, Black Bows Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Former American footballer Reggie
Torian stole the limelight of the British Grand Prix athletics
championships in Sheffield, England on Sunday, beating world
record holder Colin Jackson and Olympic champion Allen Johnson in
high hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain's Olympic silver medalist Roger Black, who
ended a bitter and controversial last week of his running
career,could only manage for a third place in the men's 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
Torian, who has burst onto the athletics scene this year after
concentrating on football until 1997, won a tight finish to the
110 hurdles in 13.15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, also the reigning world champion, dipped behind in
13.22 with Jackson third in 13.24. But Torian, the fastest racer
in the world in the discipline this year, had time to raise his
arm in celebration as he crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
"When I got to Sheffield I thought that someone had stolen the
sun. But I guess God stole it back and shone it on my performance
today," said Torian.
</P>
<P>
"I was more confident than anything. It wasn't the best race,it
wasn't the best time, but everyone was there and there was no
doubt who won."
</P>
<P>
Black, 32, had hoped to finish his last season by bidding for a
third European 400 meters title in Budapest later this month.
</P>
<P>
But after being left out of the British team for the individual
400m at the championships following a defeat at the national
trials last month, the 1986 and 1990 European champion decided to
finish his career on Sunday in front of his home fans.
</P>
<P>
In the last race of his career, the Briton could only finish
third behind his team rivals Mark Richardson and Twan Thomas.
</P>
<P>
Richardson was timed in 45.05 seconds, Thomas was second at
45.22 and Black in 45.51.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Paula Radcliffe notched up an emphatic 3,000 meters
victory over her distance rival Sonia O'Sullivan of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Radcliffe, who is expected to clash with the Irish former world
champion over 10,000 meters at the Budapest championships,burst
away from the rest of the field after three laps and was soon a
good 30 meters away.
</P>
<P>
The Briton kept the lead to finish in eight minutes 38.84
seconds with O'Sullivan well behind in second in 8:45.35. But
Radcliffe, boosted by some recent altitude training, said she
expected a bigger challenge from O'Sullivan in Budapest.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure she'll be there at the Europeans," the Briton said,
"I would never write her off because she'll just bounce right
back."
</P>
<P>
France's world 400 meters hurdles champion Stephane Diagana
bounced back from injury with his first victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
Diagana, who has struggled with calf and groin problems for the
first months of the season, clocked 48.70 seconds to record a
victory ahead of the European championships.
</P>
<P>
The world champion never looked in danger of losing the race
after he powered off the final bend a few strides ahead of the
rest of the field. Zimbabwe's Kenneth Harnden was second in 48.90
with Australian Rohan Robinson third in 49.02.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's world cross-country champion Paul Tergat also showed
his sharpness with a strong burst off the final bend to win the
men's 3,000 metres in seven minutes 39.50 seconds.
</P>
<P>
American Melissa Morrisson produced a flowing performance to
continue her superb season by winning the women's 100 hurdles in
12.74 seconds ahead of Jamaica's Michelle Freeman, the world
bronze medallist, who finished second in 12.80. 
</P>
</TEXT>
