<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corser Wins Ninth Round of Superbike Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Austrialian rider Troy Corser, who
overcame early tyre problems to dominate the second of the day's
two races, stretched his lead in the World Superbike Championships
in Brands Hatch on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Corser, who set pole in the rain on Saturday, had a frustrating
first race but his win in the second left him on 275.5 points in
the championship, ahead of the Honda-riding New Zealander Aaron
Slight on 245.
</P>
<P>
Texan Colin Edwards held off Slight for victory in the first
race as the works Ducatis hit tyre trouble with local hero Carl
Fogarty finishing fourth and Corser a distant seventh.
</P>
<P>
The Ducati mechanics solved the problems between the races and
Corser never looked in trouble over the 25 laps as he led from the
start.
</P>
<P>
"In the first race the tyres just weren't up to it...I thought
it best just to finish and get some points," said Corser, a former
Suzuki 500cc world championship rider.
</P>
<P>
"It's a shame I lost so many points (to Slight) in the first
race but I think I just made them up again," Corser said.
</P>
<P>
The second race was fairly processional for Corser but the
first was a real battle with Honda's Edwards being pushed by his
team mate Slight all the way to the flag.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't easy. I had Aaron to worry about all time. The whole
race was flat out," said Edwards, whose two other race wins this
season came at Monza in Italy in May.
</P>
<P>
"I think if I had tried something special on that last lap,I
might have taken us both out," said Slight, who crashed heavily in
the last round at Laguna Seca. Scott Russell of the United States
was third on a Yamaha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
